# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-institute-of-electrical-engineers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father, grandfather, and brother had all been associated with work on elocution and speech, and both his mother and wife were deaf, profoundly influencing Bell's life's work.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His research on hearing and speech further led him to experiment with hearing devices, which eventually culminated in his being awarded the first U.S. patent for the telephone, on March 7, 1876.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell considered his invention an intrusion on his real work as a scientist and refused to have a telephone in his study.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Many other inventions marked Bell's later life, including ground-breaking work in optical telecommunications, hydrofoils, and aeronautics.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell also had a strong influence on the National Geographic Society and its magazine while serving as its second president from 1898 to 1903.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For *National Geographic*, Bell wrote under the pseudonym **H.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Beyond his work in engineering, Bell had a deep interest in the emerging science of heredity.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His work in this area has been called "the soundest, and most useful study of human heredity proposed in nineteenth-century America ...
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was born in Edinburgh, Scotland, on March 3, 1847, to Alexander Melville Bell, a phonetician, and Eliza Grace Bell (née Symonds).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The family home was on South Charlotte Street in Edinburgh, where a stone inscription marks it as Bell's birthplace.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He had two brothers: Melville James Bell (1845–1870) and Edward Charles Bell (1848–1867), who both died of tuberculosis.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 10, however, he made a plea to his father to have a middle name like his two brothers.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For his 11th birthday, his father acquiesced and allowed him to adopt the name "Graham", chosen out of respect for Alexander Graham, a Canadian being treated by his father who was also a family friend.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] To close relatives and friends he remained "Aleck".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his siblings attended a Presbyterian Church in their youth.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As a child, Bell displayed a curiosity about his world; he gathered botanical specimens and ran experiments at an early age.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His best friend was Ben Herdman, a neighbour whose family operated a flour mill.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At the age of 12, Bell built a homemade device that combined rotating paddles with sets of nail brushes, creating a simple dehusking machine that was put into operation at the mill and used steadily for a number of years.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In return, Ben's father John Herdman gave both boys the run of a small workshop in which to "invent".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] From his early years, Bell showed a sensitive nature and a talent for art, poetry, and music that his mother encouraged.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With no formal training, he mastered the piano and became the family's pianist.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Though normally quiet and introspective, he revelled in mimicry and "voice tricks" akin to ventriloquism that entertained family guests.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was also deeply affected by his mother's gradual deafness (she began to lose her hearing when he was 12), and learned a manual finger language so he could sit at her side and tap out silently the conversations swirling around the family parlour.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also developed a technique of speaking in clear, modulated tones directly into his mother's forehead, whereby she would hear him with reasonable clarity.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's preoccupation with his mother's deafness led him to study acoustics.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His family was long associated with the teaching of elocution: his grandfather, Alexander Bell, in London, his uncle in Dublin, and his father, in Edinburgh, were all elocutionists.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father published a variety of works on the subject, several of which are still well known, especially *The Standard Elocutionist* (1860), which appeared in Edinburgh in 1868.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] *The Standard Elocutionist* appeared in 168 British editions and sold over 250,000 copies in the United States alone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It explains methods to instruct deaf-mutes (as they were then known) to articulate words and read other people's lip movements to decipher meaning.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father taught him and his brothers not only to write Visible Speech but to identify any symbol and its accompanying sound.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell became so proficient that he became a part of his father's public demonstrations and astounded audiences with his abilities.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He could decipher Visible Speech representing virtually every language, including Latin, Scottish Gaelic, and even Sanskrit, accurately reciting written tracts without any prior knowledge of their pronunciation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As a young child, Bell, like his brothers, was schooled at home by his father.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At an early age, he was enrolled at the Royal High School in Edinburgh.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But he left at age 15, having completed only the first four forms.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His school record was undistinguished, marked by absenteeism and lacklustre grades.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His main interest remained in the sciences, especially biology, while he treated other school subjects with indifference, to his father's dismay.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon leaving school, Bell travelled to London to live with his grandfather, Alexander Bell, on Harrington Square.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During the year he spent with his grandfather, a love of learning was born, with long hours spent in serious discussion and study.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The elder Bell took great efforts to have his young pupil learn to speak clearly and with conviction, attributes he would need to become a teacher himself.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 16, Bell secured a position as a "pupil-teacher" of elocution and music at Weston House Academy in Elgin, Moray, Scotland.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although enrolled as a student in Latin and Greek, he instructed classes himself in return for board and £10 per session.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The next year, he attended the University of Edinburgh, joining his brother Melville, who had enrolled there the previous year.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1868, Bell completed his matriculation exams and was accepted for admission to University College London, though he did not complete his studies, as his family emigrated to Canada in 1870 following the deaths of his brothers Edward and Melville from tuberculosis.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father encouraged his interest in speech and, in 1863, took his sons to see a unique automaton developed by Sir Charles Wheatstone based on the earlier work of Baron Wolfgang von Kempelen.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The rudimentary "mechanical man" simulated a human voice.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was fascinated by the machine, and after he obtained a copy of von Kempelen's book, published in German, and had laboriously translated it, he and Melville built their own automaton head.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Their father, highly interested in their project, offered to pay for any supplies and spurred the boys on with the enticement of a "big prize" if they were successful.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While his brother constructed the throat and larynx, Bell tackled the more difficult task of recreating a realistic skull.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His efforts resulted in a remarkably lifelike head that could "speak", albeit only a few words.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The boys would carefully adjust the "lips" and when a bellows forced air through the windpipe, a very recognizable *Mama* ensued, to the delight of neighbours who came to see the invention.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Intrigued by the results of the automaton, Bell continued to experiment with a live subject, the family's Skye Terrier, Trouve.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After he taught it to growl continuously, Bell would reach into its mouth and manipulate the dog's lips and vocal cords to produce a crude-sounding "Ow ah oo ga ma ma".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With little convincing, visitors believed his dog could articulate "How are you, grandmama?" Indicative of his playful nature, his experiments convinced onlookers that they saw a "talking dog".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These initial forays into experimentation with sound led Bell to undertake his first serious work on the transmission of sound, using tuning forks to explore resonance.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At age 19, Bell wrote a report on his work and sent it to philologist Alexander Ellis, a colleague of his father.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Ellis immediately wrote back indicating that the experiments were similar to existing work in Germany, and also lent Bell a copy of Hermann von Helmholtz's work, *The Sensations of Tone as a Physiological Basis for the Theory of Music*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Dismayed to find that groundbreaking work had already been undertaken by Helmholtz, who had conveyed vowel sounds by means of a similar tuning fork "contraption", Bell pored over the book.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1865, when the Bell family moved to London, Bell returned to Weston House as an assistant master and, in his spare hours, continued experiments on sound using a minimum of laboratory equipment.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell concentrated on experimenting with electricity to convey sound and later installed a telegraph wire from his room in Somerset College to that of a friend.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Throughout late 1867, his health faltered mainly through exhaustion.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His brother Edward was similarly affected by tuberculosis.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While Bell recovered (by then referring to himself in correspondence as "A.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell") and served the next year as an instructor at Somerset College, Bath, England, his brother's condition deteriorated.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon his brother's death, Bell returned home in 1867.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With aspirations to obtain a degree at University College London, Bell considered his next years preparation for the degree examinations, devoting his spare time to studying.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Helping his father in Visible Speech demonstrations and lectures brought Bell to Susanna E.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Hull's private school for the deaf in South Kensington, London.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His first two pupils were deaf-mute girls who made remarkable progress under his tutelage.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While Melville seemed to achieve success on many fronts, including opening his own elocution school, applying for a patent on an invention, and starting a family, Bell continued as a teacher.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In May 1870, Melville died from complications of tuberculosis, causing a family crisis.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father had also experienced a debilitating illness earlier in life and been restored to health by convalescence in Newfoundland.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's parents embarked upon a long-planned move when they realized that their remaining son was also sickly.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Acting decisively, Alexander Melville Bell asked Bell to arrange for the sale of all the family property, conclude all his brother's affairs (Bell took on his last student, curing a pronounced lisp), and join his father and mother in setting out for Canada.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Reluctantly, Bell also had to conclude a relationship with Marie Eccleston, who, as he had surmised, was not prepared to leave England with him.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1870, 23-year-old Bell travelled with his parents and his brother's widow, Caroline Margaret Ottaway, to Paris, Ontario, to stay with Thomas Henderson, a Baptist minister and family friend.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bells soon purchased a farm of 10.5 acres (4.2 ha) at Tutelo Heights (now called Tutela Heights), near Brantford, Ontario.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The property consisted of an orchard, large farmhouse, stable, pigsty, hen-house, and a carriage house, which bordered the Grand River.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At the homestead, Bell set up a workshop in the converted carriage house near what he called his "dreaming place", a large hollow nestled in trees at the back of the property above the river.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Despite his frail condition upon arriving in Canada, Bell found the climate and environs to his liking and rapidly improved.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He continued his interest in the study of the human voice, and when he discovered the Six Nations Reserve across the river at Onondaga, learned the Mohawk language and translated its unwritten vocabulary into Visible Speech symbols.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] For his work, Bell was awarded the title of Honorary Chief and participated in a ceremony where he donned a Mohawk headdress and danced traditional dances.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After setting up his workshop, Bell continued experiments based on Helmholtz's work with electricity and sound.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also modified a melodeon (a type of pump organ) to transmit its music electrically over a distance.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Once the family was settled, Bell and his father made plans to establish a teaching practice and in 1871, he accompanied his father to Montreal, where Melville was offered a position to teach his System of Visible Speech.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's father was invited by Sarah Fuller, principal of the Boston School for Deaf Mutes (later to become the public Horace Mann School for the Deaf) to introduce the Visible Speech System by providing training for Fuller's instructors, but he declined the post in favour of his son.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Travelling to Boston in April 1871, Bell proved successful in training the school's instructors.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He was asked to repeat the programme at the American Asylum for Deaf-mutes in Hartford, Connecticut, and the Clarke School for the Deaf in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning home to Brantford after six months abroad, Bell continued his experiments with his "harmonic telegraph".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The basic concept behind his device was that messages could be sent through a single wire if each was transmitted at a different pitch, but work on both the transmitter and receiver was needed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Unsure of his future, he contemplated returning to London to complete his studies, but decided to return to Boston as a teacher.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His father helped him set up his private practice by contacting Gardiner Greene Hubbard, the president of the Clarke School for the Deaf for a recommendation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Teaching his father's system, in October 1872, Alexander Bell opened his "School of Vocal Physiology and Mechanics of Speech" in Boston, which attracted a large number of deaf pupils, with his first class numbering 30 students.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While he was working as a private tutor, one of his pupils was Helen Keller, who came to him as a young child unable to see, hear, or speak.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] She later said that Bell dedicated his life to the penetration of that "inhuman silence which separates and estranges".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1893, Keller performed the sod-breaking ceremony for the construction of Bell's new Volta Bureau, dedicated to "the increase and diffusion of knowledge relating to the deaf".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1891, Bell established the American Association for the Promotion of the Teaching of Speech to the Deaf (AAPTSD) in New York and endowed the organization with a gift of $25,000.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While endorsing the teaching of speech to the deaf, Bell remained neutral as to whether oral, manual or a combination of the three methods would best benefit the student.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Throughout his life, Bell sought to assimilate the deaf and hard of hearing with the broader population.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He encouraged speech therapy and lip-reading as well as sign language.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He outlined this in an 1898 paper detailing his belief that, with resources and effort, the deaf could be taught to read lips and speak (known as oralism), enabling their integration with wider society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Members of the Deaf community have criticized Bell for supporting lip-reading over the use of sign language.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1872, Bell became professor of Vocal Physiology and Elocution at the Boston University School of Oratory.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During this period, he alternated between Boston and Brantford, spending summers in his Canadian home.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At Boston University, Bell was "swept up" by the excitement engendered by the many scientists and inventors living in the city.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He continued his research in sound and endeavoured to find a way to transmit musical notes and articulate speech, but although absorbed by his experiments, he found it difficult to devote enough time to experimentation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With days and evenings occupied by his teaching and private classes, Bell began to stay awake late into the night, running experiment after experiment in rented facilities at his boarding house.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Keeping "night owl" hours, he worried that his work would be discovered and took great pains to lock up his notebooks and laboratory equipment.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell had a specially made table where he could place his notes and equipment inside a locking cover.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His health deteriorated as he had severe headaches.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning to Boston in autumn 1873, Bell made a far-reaching decision to concentrate on his experiments in sound.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Giving up his lucrative private Boston practice, Bell retained only two students, six-year-old "Georgie" Sanders, deaf from birth, and 15-year-old Mabel Hubbard.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Each played an important role in the next developments.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Georgie's father, Thomas Sanders, a wealthy businessman, offered Bell a place to stay in nearby Salem with Georgie's grandmother, complete with a room to "experiment".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the offer was made by Georgie's mother and followed the year-long arrangement in 1872 where her son and his nurse had moved to quarters next to Bell's boarding house, it was clear that Mr.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The arrangement was for teacher and student to continue their work together, with free room and board thrown in.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Mabel was a bright, attractive girl ten years Bell's junior who became the object of his affection.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Having lost her hearing after a near-fatal bout of scarlet fever close to her fifth birthday, she had learned to read lips but her father, Gardiner Greene Hubbard, Bell's benefactor and personal friend, wanted her to work directly with her teacher.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1874, Bell's initial work on the harmonic telegraph had entered a formative stage, with progress made both at his new Boston "laboratory" (a rented facility) and at his family home in Canada a big success.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] While working that summer in Brantford, Bell experimented with a "phonautograph", a pen-like machine that could draw shapes of sound waves on smoked glass by tracing their vibrations.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell thought it might be possible to generate undulating electrical currents that would correspond to sound waves.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also believed that he would be able to convert the undulating currents back into sound by tuning multiple metal reeds to different frequencies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But he had no working model to demonstrate the feasibility of these ideas.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1874, telegraph message traffic was rapidly expanding and, in the words of Western Union President William Orton, had become "the nervous system of commerce".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Orton had contracted with inventors Thomas Edison and Elisha Gray to find a way to send multiple telegraph messages on each telegraph line to avoid the great cost of constructing new lines.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell mentioned to Gardiner Hubbard and Thomas Sanders that he was working on a method of sending multiple tones on a telegraph wire using a multi-reed device, the two began to financially support Bell's experiments.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent matters were handled by Hubbard's patent attorney, Anthony Pollok.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In March 1875, Bell and Pollok visited the scientist Joseph Henry, then the director of the Smithsonian Institution, to ask his advice on the electrical multi-reed apparatus that Bell hoped would transmit the human voice by telegraph.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Henry said Bell had "the germ of a great invention".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell said that he lacked the necessary knowledge, Henry replied, "Get it!" That declaration greatly encouraged Bell to keep trying, even though he had neither the equipment needed to continue his experiments nor the ability to create a working model of his ideas.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But a chance meeting in 1874 between Bell and Thomas A.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson, an experienced electrical designer and mechanic at the electrical machine shop of Charles Williams, changed that.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With financial support from Sanders and Hubbard, Bell hired Watson as his assistant, and the two experimented with acoustic telegraphy.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On June 2, 1875, Watson accidentally plucked one of the reeds and Bell, at the receiving end of the wire, heard the reed's overtones that would be necessary for transmitting speech.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That demonstrated to Bell that only one reed or armature was necessary, not multiple reeds.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This led to the "gallows" sound-powered telephone, which could transmit indistinct, voice-like sounds, but not clear speech.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1875, Bell developed an acoustic telegraph and drew up a patent application for it.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meanwhile, Elisha Gray was also experimenting with acoustic telegraphy and thought of a way to transmit speech using a water transmitter.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On February 14, 1876, Gray filed a caveat with the U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent Office for a telephone design that used a water transmitter.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That same morning, Bell's lawyer filed Bell's application with the patent office.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] There is considerable debate about who arrived first and Gray later challenged the primacy of Bell's patent.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was in Boston on February 14 and did not arrive in Washington until February 26.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Patent Office issued Bell patent 174,465.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 10, Bell succeeded in getting his telephone to work, using a liquid transmitter similar to Gray's design.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Vibration of the diaphragm caused a needle to vibrate in the water, varying the electrical resistance in the circuit.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson—Come here—I want to see you" into the liquid transmitter, Watson, listening at the receiving end in an adjoining room, heard the words clearly.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After March 1876, Bell focused on improving the electromagnetic telephone and never used Gray's liquid transmitter in public demonstrations or commercial use.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The examiner raised the question of priority for the variable resistance feature of the telephone before approving Bell's patent application.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He told Bell that his claim for the variable resistance feature was also described in Gray's caveat.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell pointed to a variable resistance device in his previous application in which he described a cup of mercury, not water.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He had filed the mercury application at the patent office on February 25, 1875, long before Gray described the water device.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In addition, Gray abandoned his caveat, and because he did not contest Bell's priority, the examiner approved Bell's patent on March 3, 1876.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Gray had reinvented the variable resistance telephone, but Bell was the first to write down the idea and test it in a telephone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The patent examiner, Zenas Fisk Wilber, later stated in an affidavit that he was an alcoholic who was much in debt to Bell's lawyer, Marcellus Bailey, with whom he had served in the Civil War.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He said he had shown Bailey Gray's patent caveat.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Wilber also said (after Bell arrived in Washington D.C. from Boston) that he showed Bell Gray's caveat and that Bell paid him $100 (equivalent to $2,900 in 2025).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell said they discussed the patent only in general terms, although in a letter to Gray, Bell admitted that he learned some of the technical details.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell denied in an affidavit that he ever gave Wilber any money.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 10, 1876, Bell used "the instrument" in Boston to call Thomas Watson who was in another room but out of earshot.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Watson, come here – I want to see you" and Watson soon appeared at his side.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Continuing his experiments in Brantford, Bell brought home a working model of his telephone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On August 3, 1876, from the telegraph office in Brantford, Bell sent a telegram to the village of Mount Pleasant four miles (six kilometres) away, indicating that he was ready.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He made a telephone call via telegraph wires and faint voices were heard replying.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The following night, he amazed guests as well as his family with a call between the Bell Homestead and the office of the Dominion Telegraph Company in Brantford along an improvised wire strung up along telegraph lines and fences, and laid through a tunnel.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This time, guests at the household distinctly heard people in Brantford reading and singing.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The third test, on August 10, 1876, was made via the telegraph line between Brantford and Paris, Ontario, eight miles (thirteen kilometres) away.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This test is said by many sources to be the "world's first long-distance call".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It proved that the telephone could work over long distances, at least as a one-way call.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The first two-way (reciprocal) conversation over a line occurred between Cambridge and Boston (roughly 2.5 miles) on October 9, 1876.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During that conversation, Bell was on Kilby Street in Boston and Watson was at the offices of the Walworth Manufacturing Company.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his partners, Hubbard and Sanders, offered to sell the patent outright to Western Union for $100,000, equal to $3,023,438 today, but it did not work (according to an apocryphal story, the president of Western Union balked, countering that the telephone was nothing but a toy).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Two years later, he told colleagues that if he could get the patent for $25 million (equal to $834,051,724 today), he would consider it a bargain.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By then, the Bell company no longer wanted to sell the patent.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's investors became millionaires while he fared well from residuals and at one point had assets of nearly $1 million.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell began a series of public demonstrations and lectures to introduce the new invention to the scientific community as well as the general public.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] A short time later, his demonstration of an early telephone prototype at the 1876 Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia brought the telephone to international attention.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Influential visitors to the exhibition included Emperor Pedro II of Brazil.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the judges at the Exhibition, Sir William Thomson (later Lord Kelvin), a renowned Scottish scientist, described the telephone as "the greatest by far of all the marvels of the electric telegraph".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On January 14, 1878, at Osborne House, on the Isle of Wight, Bell demonstrated the device to Queen Victoria, placing calls to Cowes, Southampton, and London.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These were the first publicly witnessed long-distance telephone calls in the UK.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The queen found the process "quite extraordinary" although the sound was "rather faint".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] She later asked to buy the equipment that was used, but Bell offered to make "a set of telephones" specifically for her.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell Telephone Company was created in 1877, and by 1886, more than 150,000 people in the U.S. owned telephones.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell Company engineers made numerous other improvements to the telephone, which emerged as one of the most successful products ever.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1879, the company acquired Edison's patents for the carbon microphone from Western Union.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This made the telephone practical for longer distances, and it was no longer necessary to shout to be heard at the receiving telephone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pedro II of Brazil was the first person to buy stock in the Bell Telephone Company.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the first telephones in a private residence was installed in his palace in Petrópolis, his summer retreat forty miles (sixty-four kilometres) from Rio de Janeiro.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In January 1915, Bell made the first ceremonial transcontinental telephone call.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Calling from the AT&T head office at 15 Dey Street in New York City, Bell was heard by Thomas Watson at 333 Grant Avenue in San Francisco.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] As is sometimes common in scientific discoveries, simultaneous developments occurred, as evidenced by a number of inventors who were at work on the telephone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Over 18 years, the Bell Telephone Company faced 587 court challenges to its patents, including five that went to the U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Supreme Court, but none was successful in establishing priority over Bell's original patent, and the Bell Telephone Company never lost a case that had proceeded to a final trial stage.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's laboratory notes and family letters were the key to establishing a long lineage to his experiments.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell company lawyers successfully fought off myriad lawsuits generated initially around the challenges by Elisha Gray and Amos Dolbear.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In personal correspondence to Bell, both Gray and Dolbear had acknowledged his prior work, which considerably weakened their later claims.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On January 13, 1887, the U.S. government moved to annul the patent issued to Bell on the grounds of fraud and misrepresentation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After a series of decisions and reversals, the Bell company won a decision in the Supreme Court, though a couple of the original claims from the lower court cases were left undecided.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By the time the trial had wound its way through nine years of legal battles, the U.S. prosecuting attorney had died and the two Bell patents (No.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] 186,787, dated January 30, 1877) were no longer in effect, although the presiding judges agreed to continue the proceedings due to the case's importance as a precedent.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With a change in administration and charges of conflict of interest (on both sides) arising from the original trial, the U.S. attorney general dropped the lawsuit on November 30, 1897, leaving several issues undecided on the merits.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During a deposition filed for the 1887 trial, Italian inventor Antonio Meucci also claimed to have created the first working model of a telephone in Italy in 1834.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1886, in the first of three cases in which he was involved, Meucci took the stand as a witness in hope of establishing his invention's priority.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meucci's testimony was disputed due to lack of material evidence for his inventions, as his working models were purportedly lost at the laboratory of American District Telegraph (ADT) of New York, which was incorporated as a subsidiary of Western Union in 1901.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meucci's work, like that of many other inventors of the period, was based on earlier acoustic principles and, despite evidence of earlier experiments, the final case involving Meucci was eventually dropped upon Meucci's death.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] But due to the efforts of Congressman Vito Fossella, on June 11, 2002, the U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] House of Representatives stated that Meucci's "work in the invention of the telephone should be acknowledged".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This did not put an end to the still contentious issue.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Some modern scholars do not agree that Bell's work on the telephone was influenced by Meucci's inventions.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The value of Bell's patent was acknowledged throughout the world, and patent applications were made in most major countries.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] When Bell delayed the German patent application, the electrical firm Siemens & Halske set up a rival manufacturer of Bell telephones under its own patent.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Siemens produced near-identical copies of the Bell telephone without having to pay royalties.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The establishment of the International Bell Telephone Company in Brussels, Belgium, in 1880, as well as a series of agreements in other countries eventually consolidated a global telephone operation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The strain put on Bell by his constant appearances in court, necessitated by the legal battles, eventually resulted in his resignation from the company.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On July 11, 1877, a few days after the Bell Telephone Company was established, Bell married Mabel Hubbard (1857–1923) at the Hubbard estate in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] His wedding present to his bride was to turn over 1,487 of his 1,497 shares in the newly formed Bell Telephone Company.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Shortly thereafter, the newly-weds embarked on a year-long honeymoon in Europe.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During that excursion, Bell took a handmade model of his telephone with him, making it a "working holiday".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The courtship had begun years earlier; however, Bell waited until he was more financially secure before marrying.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the telephone appeared to be an "instant" success, it was not initially a profitable venture and Bell's main sources of income were from lectures until after 1897.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One unusual request exacted by his fiancée was that he use "Alec" rather than the family's earlier familiar name of "Aleck".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] From 1876, he would sign his name "Alec Bell".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bell family home was in Cambridge, Massachusetts, until 1880 when Bell's father-in-law bought a house in Washington, D.C.; in 1882 he bought a home in the same city for Bell's family, so they could be with him while he attended to the numerous court cases involving patent disputes.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was a British subject throughout his early life in Scotland and later in Canada until 1882 when he became a naturalized citizen of the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1915, he characterized his status as: "I am not one of those hyphenated Americans who claim allegiance to two countries." Despite this declaration, Bell has been proudly claimed as a "native son" by all three countries he resided in: the United States, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1885, a new summer retreat was contemplated.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] That summer, the Bells had a vacation on Cape Breton Island in Nova Scotia, Canada, spending time at the small village of Baddeck.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Returning in 1886, Bell started building an estate on a point across from Baddeck, overlooking Bras d'Or Lake.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] By 1889, a large house, christened *The Lodge* was completed and two years later, a larger complex of buildings, including a new laboratory, were begun that the Bells would name Beinn Bhreagh (Gaelic: *Beautiful Mountain*) after Bell's ancestral Scottish Highlands.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell also built the Bell Boatyard on the estate, employing up to 40 people building experimental craft as well as wartime lifeboats and workboats for the Royal Canadian Navy and pleasure craft for the Bell family.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He was an enthusiastic boater, and Bell and his family sailed or rowed a long series of vessels on Bras d'Or Lake, ordering additional vessels from the H.W.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Embree and Sons boatyard in Port Hawkesbury, Nova Scotia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In his final, and some of his most productive years, Bell split his residency between Washington, D.C., where he and his family initially resided for most of the year, and Beinn Bhreagh, where they spent increasing amounts of time.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Until the end of his life, Bell and his family would alternate between the two homes, but *Beinn Bhreagh* would, over the next 30 years, become more than a summer home as Bell became so absorbed in his experiments that his annual stays lengthened.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Both Mabel and Bell became immersed in the Baddeck community and were accepted by the villagers as "their own".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The Bells were still in residence at *Beinn Bhreagh* when the Halifax Explosion occurred on December 6, 1917.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Mabel and Bell mobilized the community to help victims in Halifax.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although Alexander Graham Bell is most often associated with the invention of the telephone, his interests were extremely varied.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] According to one of his biographers, Charlotte Gray, Bell's work ranged "unfettered across the scientific landscape" and he often went to bed voraciously reading the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, scouring it for new areas of interest.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The range of Bell's inventive genius is represented only in part by the 18 patents granted in his name alone and the 12 he shared with his collaborators.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] These included 14 for the telephone and telegraph, four for the photophone, one for the phonograph, five for aerial vehicles, four for "hydroairplanes", and two for selenium cells.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's inventions spanned a wide range of interests and included a metal jacket to assist in breathing, the audiometer to detect minor hearing problems, a device to locate icebergs, investigations on how to separate salt from seawater, and work on finding alternative fuels.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell worked extensively in medical research and invented techniques for teaching speech to the deaf.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During his Volta Laboratory period, Bell and his associates considered impressing a magnetic field on a record as a means of reproducing sound.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Although the trio briefly experimented with the concept, they could not develop a workable prototype.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] They abandoned the idea, never realizing they had glimpsed a basic principle which would one day find its application in the tape recorder, the hard disc and floppy disc drive, and other magnetic media.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's own home used a primitive form of air conditioning, in which fans blew currents of air across great blocks of ice.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] He also anticipated modern concerns with fuel shortages and industrial pollution.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Methane gas, he reasoned, could be produced from the waste of farms and factories.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] At his Canadian estate in Nova Scotia, he experimented with composting toilets and devices to capture water from the atmosphere.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In a magazine article published in 1917, he reflected on the possibility of using solar energy to heat houses.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell and his assistant Charles Sumner Tainter jointly invented a wireless telephone, named a photophone, which allowed for the transmission of both sounds and normal human conversations on a beam of light.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Both men later became full associates in the Volta Laboratory Association.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On June 21, 1880, Bell's assistant transmitted a wireless voice telephone message a considerable distance, from the roof of the Franklin School in Washington, D.C., to Bell at the window of his laboratory, some 700 feet (213 m) away, 19 years before the first voice radio transmissions.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell believed the photophone's principles were his life's "greatest achievement", telling a reporter shortly before his death that the photophone was "the greatest invention [I have] ever made, greater than the telephone".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The photophone was a precursor to the fiber-optic communication systems which achieved popular worldwide usage in the 1980s.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Its master patent was issued in December 1880, many decades before the photophone's principles came into popular use.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell is also credited with developing one of the early versions of a metal detector through the use of an induction balance, after the shooting of U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] According to some accounts, the metal detector worked flawlessly in tests but did not find Guiteau's bullet, partly because the metal bed frame on which the President was lying disturbed the instrument, resulting in static.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Garfield's surgeons, led by self-appointed chief physician Doctor Willard Bliss, were sceptical of the device, and ignored Bell's requests to move the President to a bed not fitted with metal springs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Alternatively, although Bell had detected a slight sound on his first test, the bullet may have been lodged too deeply to be detected by the crude apparatus.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell's own detailed account, presented to the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1882, differs in several particulars from most of the many and varied versions now in circulation, by concluding that extraneous metal was not to blame for failure to locate the bullet.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Perplexed by the peculiar results he had obtained during an examination of Garfield, Bell "proceeded to the Executive Mansion the next morning ... to ascertain from the surgeons whether they were perfectly sure that all metal had been removed from the neighborhood of the bed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] It was then recollected that underneath the horse-hair mattress on which the President lay was another mattress composed of steel wires.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Upon obtaining a duplicate, the mattress was found to consist of a sort of net of woven steel wires, with large meshes.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The March 1906 *Scientific American* article by American pioneer William E.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Meacham explained the basic principle of hydrofoils and hydroplanes.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell considered the invention of the hydroplane as a very significant achievement.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Based on information gained from that article, he began to sketch concepts of what is now called a hydrofoil boat.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] "Casey" Baldwin began hydrofoil experimentation in the summer of 1908 as a possible aid to airplane takeoff from water.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin studied the work of the Italian inventor Enrico Forlanini and began testing models.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] This led him and Bell to the development of practical hydrofoil watercraft.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] During his world tour of 1910–11, Bell and Baldwin met with Forlanini in France.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] They had rides in the Forlanini hydrofoil boat over Lake Maggiore.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin described it as being as smooth as flying.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On returning to Baddeck, a number of initial concepts were built as experimental models, including the *Dhonnas Beag* (Scottish Gaelic for 'little devil'), the first self-propelled Bell-Baldwin hydrofoil.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The experimental boats were essentially proof-of-concept prototypes that culminated in the more substantial HD-4, powered by Renault engines.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] A top speed of 54 miles per hour (87 km/h) was achieved, with the hydrofoil exhibiting rapid acceleration, good stability, and steering, along with the ability to take waves without difficulty.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell hired Walter Pinaud, a Sydney yacht designer and builder as well as the proprietor of Pinaud's Yacht Yard in Westmount, Nova Scotia, to work on the pontoons of the HD-4.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pinaud soon took over the boatyard at Bell Laboratories on Beinn Bhreagh, Bell's estate near Baddeck, Nova Scotia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Pinaud's experience in boatbuilding enabled him to make useful design changes to the HD-4.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] After the First World War, work began again on the HD-4.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Navy permitted him to obtain two 350-horsepower (260-kilowatt) engines in July 1919.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On September 9, 1919, the HD-4 set a world marine speed record of 70.86 miles per hour (114.04 kilometres per hour), a record which stood for one year.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1891, Bell had begun experiments to develop motor-powered heavier-than-air aircraft.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA was first formed as Bell shared the vision to fly with his wife, who advised him to seek "young" help as Bell was at the age of 60.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] In 1898, Bell experimented with tetrahedral box kites and wings constructed of multiple compound tetrahedral kites covered in maroon silk.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The tetrahedral wings were named *Cygnet* I, II, and III, and were flown both unmanned and manned (*Cygnet I* crashed during a flight carrying Selfridge) in the period from 1907 to 1912.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Some of Bell's kites are on display at the Alexander Graham Bell National Historic Site.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell was a supporter of aerospace engineering research through the Aerial Experiment Association (AEA), officially formed at Baddeck, Nova Scotia, in October 1907 at the suggestion of his wife Mabel and with her financial support after the sale of some of her real estate.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA was headed by Bell and the founding members were four young men: American Glenn H.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Federal government and one of the few people in the army who believed that aviation was the future; Frederick W.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Baldwin, the first Canadian and first British subject to pilot a public flight in Hammondsport, New York; and J.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] McCurdy–Baldwin and McCurdy being new engineering graduates from the University of Toronto.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The AEA's work progressed to heavier-than-air machines, applying their knowledge of kites to gliders.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Moving to Hammondsport, the group then designed and built the *Red Wing*, framed in bamboo and covered in red silk and powered by a small air-cooled engine.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On March 12, 1908, over Keuka Lake, the biplane lifted off on the first public flight in North America.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The innovations that were incorporated into this design included a cockpit enclosure and tail rudder (later variations on the original design would add ailerons as a means of control).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] One of the AEA's inventions, a practical wingtip form of the aileron, was to become a standard component on all aircraft.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] The *White Wing* and *June Bug* were to follow and by the end of 1908, over 150 flights without mishap had been accomplished.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] However, the AEA had depleted its initial reserves and only a $15,000 grant from Mrs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell allowed it to continue with experiments.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Selfridge had also become the first person killed in a powered heavier-than-air flight in a crash of the Wright Flyer at Fort Myer, Virginia, on September 17, 1908.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Their final aircraft design, the *Silver Dart*, embodied all of the advancements found in the earlier machines.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] On February 23, 1909, Bell was present as the *Silver Dart* flown by J.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] McCurdy from the frozen ice of Bras d'Or made the first aircraft flight in Canada.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] Bell had worried that the flight was too dangerous and had arranged for a doctor to be on hand.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p01] With the successful flight, the AEA disbanded and the *Silver Dart* would revert to Baldwin and McCurdy, who began the Canadian Aerodrome Company and would later demonstrate the aircraft to the Canadian Army.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell, along with many members of the scientific community at the time, took an interest in the popular science of heredity which grew out of the publication of Charles Darwin's book *On the Origin of Species* in 1859.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] On his estate in Nova Scotia, Bell conducted meticulously recorded breeding experiments with rams and ewes.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Over the course of more than 30 years, Bell sought to produce a breed of sheep with multiple nipples that would bear twins.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He specifically wanted to see if selective breeding could produce sheep with four functional nipples with enough milk for twin lambs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] This interest in animal breeding caught the attention of scientists focused on the study of heredity and genetics in humans.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In November 1883, Bell presented a paper at a meeting of the National Academy of Sciences titled *Upon the Formation of a Deaf Variety of the Human Race*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The paper is a compilation of data on the hereditary aspects of deafness.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's research indicated that a hereditary tendency toward deafness, as indicated by the possession of deaf relatives, was an important element in determining the production of deaf offspring.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He noted that the proportion of deaf children born to deaf parents was many times greater than the proportion of deaf children born to the general population.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In the paper, Bell delved into social commentary and discussed hypothetical public policies to bring an end to deafness.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He also criticized educational practices that segregated deaf children rather than integrating them fully into mainstream classrooms.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A review of Bell's *Memoir upon the Formation of a Deaf Variety of the Human Race* appearing in an 1885 issue of the *American Annals of the Deaf and Dumb* states that "Dr.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Historians have noted that Bell explicitly opposed laws regulating marriage, and never mentioned sterilization in any of his writings.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Even after Bell agreed to engage with scientists conducting eugenic research, he consistently refused to support public policy that limited the rights or privileges of the deaf.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's interest and research on heredity attracted the interest of Charles Davenport, a Harvard professor and head of the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1906, Davenport, who was also the founder of the American Breeder's Association, approached Bell about joining a new committee on eugenics chaired by David Starr Jordan.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1910, Davenport opened the Eugenics Records office at Cold Spring Harbor.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] To give the organization scientific credibility, Davenport set up a Board of Scientific Directors naming Bell as chairman.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Other members of the board included Luther Burbank, Roswell H.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1921, a Second International Congress of Eugenics was held in New York at the Museum of Natural History and chaired by Davenport.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Although Bell did not present any research or speak as part of the proceedings, he was named as honorary president as a means to attract other scientists to attend the event.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A summary of the event notes that Bell was a "pioneering investigator in the field of human heredity".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell died of complications arising from diabetes on August 2, 1922, at his private estate in Cape Breton, Nova Scotia, at age 75.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell had also been affected by pernicious anemia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] His last view of the land he had inhabited was by moonlight on his mountain estate at 2:00 a.m.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] While tending to him after his long illness, Mabel, his wife, whispered, "Don't leave me." By way of reply, Bell signed "no...", lost consciousness, and died shortly after.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] On learning of Bell's death, the Canadian Prime Minister, Mackenzie King, cabled Mrs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's coffin was constructed of Beinn Bhreagh pine by his laboratory staff, lined with the same red silk fabric used in his tetrahedral kite experiments.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Upon the conclusion of Bell's funeral, for one minute at 6:25 p.m.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Eastern Time, "every phone on the continent of North America was silenced in honor of the man who had given to mankind the means for direct communication at a distance".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Alexander Graham Bell was buried atop Beinn Bhreagh mountain, on his estate where he had resided increasingly for the last 35 years of his life, overlooking Bras d'Or Lake.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He was survived by his wife Mabel, his two daughters, Elsie May and Marian, and nine of his grandchildren.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Honours and tributes flowed to Bell in increasing numbers as his invention became ubiquitous and his personal fame grew.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell received numerous honorary degrees from colleges and universities to the point that the requests almost became burdensome.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] During his life, he also received dozens of major awards, medals, and other tributes.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] These included statuary monuments to both him and the new form of communication his telephone created, including the Bell Telephone Memorial erected in his honour in *Alexander Graham Bell Gardens* in Brantford, Ontario, in 1917.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] A number of historic sites and other marks commemorate Bell in North America and Europe, including the first telephone companies in the United States and Canada.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1880, Bell received the Volta Prize with a purse of 50,000 French francs (approximately US$350,000 in today's currency) for the invention of the telephone from the French government.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Among the luminaries who judged were Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Volta Prize was conceived by Napoleon III in 1852, and named in honour of Alessandro Volta, with Bell becoming the second recipient of the grand prize in its history.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Volta Laboratory became an experimental facility devoted to scientific discovery, and the very next year it improved Edison's phonograph by substituting wax for tinfoil as the recording medium and incising the recording rather than indenting it, key upgrades that Edison himself later adopted.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In partnership with Gardiner Greene Hubbard, Bell helped establish the publication *Science* during the early 1880s.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1898, Bell was elected as the second president of the National Geographic Society, serving until 1903, and was primarily responsible for the extensive use of illustrations, including photography, in the magazine.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He also served for many years as a Regent of the Smithsonian Institution (1898–1922).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] He was one of the founders of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers in 1884 and served as its president from 1891 to 1892.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell was later awarded the AIEE's Edison Medal in 1914 "For meritorious achievement in the invention of the telephone".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The *bel* (B) and the smaller *decibel* (dB) are units of measurement of sound pressure level (SPL) invented by Bell Labs and named after him.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Since 1976, the IEEE's Alexander Graham Bell Medal has been awarded to honour outstanding contributions in the field of telecommunications.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 1936, the US Patent Office declared Bell first on its list of the country's greatest inventors, leading to the US Post Office issuing a commemorative stamp honouring Bell in 1940 as part of its 'Famous Americans Series'.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The First Day of Issue ceremony was held on October 28 in Boston, Massachusetts, the city where Bell spent considerable time on research and working with the deaf.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The Bell stamp became very popular and sold out in little time.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The stamp became, and remains to this day, the most valuable one of the series.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] The 150th anniversary of Bell's birth in 1997 was marked by a special issue of commemorative £1 banknotes from the Royal Bank of Scotland.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Additionally, the Government of Canada honoured Bell in 1997 with a C$100 gold coin, in tribute also to the 150th anniversary of his birth, and with a silver dollar coin in 2009 in honour of the 100th anniversary of flight in Canada.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] That first flight was made by an airplane designed under Dr.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's image, and also those of his many inventions have graced paper money, coinage, and postal stamps in numerous countries worldwide for many dozens of years.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Alexander Graham Bell was ranked 57th among the 100 Greatest Britons (2002) in an official BBC nationwide poll, and among the Top Ten Greatest Canadians (2004), and the 100 Greatest Americans (2005).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] In 2006, Bell was also named as one of the 10 greatest Scottish scientists in history after having been listed in the National Library of Scotland's 'Scottish Science Hall of Fame'.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/alexander-graham-bell-p02] Bell's name is still widely known and used as part of the names of dozens of educational institutes, corporate namesakes, street and place names around the world.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The **American Institute of Electrical Engineers** (**AIEE**) was a United States–based organization of electrical engineers that existed from 1884 through 1962.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] On January 1, 1963, it merged with the Institute of Radio Engineers (IRE) to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The 1884 founders of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers (AIEE) included some of the most prominent inventors and innovators in the then new field of electrical engineering, among them Nikola Tesla, Thomas Alva Edison, Elihu Thomson, Edwin J.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Other notable AIEE presidents were Alexander Graham Bell (1891–1892), Charles Proteus Steinmetz (1901–1902), Bion J.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first technical meeting of the AIEE was held during the International Electrical Exhibition of 1884 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, on October 7–8, at the Franklin Institute.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] After several years of operating primarily in New York City, the AIEE authorized local sections in 1902.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] These were first formed in the United States in Chicago and Ithaca, New York, in 1902, and then in other countries.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first section outside the United States, established in 1903, was in Toronto, Canada.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] AIEE's regional structure was soon complemented by a technical structure.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The first technical committee of AIEE, the High Voltage Transmission Committee, was formed in 1903.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Standardization work started in 1891 with the formation of a committee on units and standards, followed by a committee on standard wiring.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] At the 50th anniversary of the organization, there were 10 women members, including Edith Clarke (associate member in 1923, member in 1933) and Mabel MacFerran Rockwell (associate member in 1928, member in 1935).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The formation of the AIEE Subcommittee on Large-Scale Computing in 1946 was considered a key milestone in the history of computer engineering, representing the first time that a professional association recognized the significance of computers and computing in electro-technology.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The early technical areas of interest of AIEE were electric power, lighting, and wired communications.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Radio and wireless communications became the major focus of a rival organization, the Institute of Radio Engineers (the IRE, established 1912).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The dynamic growth of radio technology and the emergence of the new discipline of electronics in the 1940s led to stiff competition between AIEE and IRE, with IRE showing faster growth in the 1950s and early 1960s, and attracting more students.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] In 1957, the IRE, with approximately 55,500 members, surpassed the AIEE in membership size; by 1962 the IRE had 96,500 members to the AIEE's 57,000.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Although the AIEE was a member-volunteer run organization, it relied on a paid staff for daily operations.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The photos that accompanied the article not only included images of the women who worked there, but unusual for the time, also named them.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Female employees of the AIEE included Miss Mary E.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] After the AIEE's founding in 1884, its member's badge was created in 1893 by a committee headed by Alexander Graham Bell, AIEE's president from 1891 to 1892.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The badge's logo depicted Benjamin Franklin's kite, representative of the discovery that lightning carried electricity.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The design also showed a winding of gold wire with its midpoints crossed by a galvanometer's indicator, invoking the electrical engineer's Wheatstone bridge.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] Ohm's law and the letters "AIEE" were added in gold at the logo's base.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The busy logo design was replaced four years later.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/american-institute-of-electrical-engineers] The AIEE and the IRE merged in 1963 to form the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), in short order becoming the world's largest technical society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Born in the Province of Massachusetts Bay, Franklin became a successful newspaper editor and printer in Philadelphia, the leading city in the colonies, publishing *The Pennsylvania Gazette* at age 23.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He became wealthy publishing this and *Poor Richard's Almanack*, which he wrote under the pseudonym "Richard Saunders".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] After 1767, he was associated with the *Pennsylvania Chronicle*, a newspaper known for its revolutionary sentiments and criticisms of the policies of the British Parliament and the Crown.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He pioneered and was the first president of the Academy and College of Philadelphia, which opened in 1751 and later became the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He organized and was the first secretary of the American Philosophical Society and was elected its president in 1769.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was appointed deputy postmaster-general for the British colonies in 1753, which enabled him to set up the first national communications network.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was active in community affairs and colonial and state politics, as well as national and international affairs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He became a hero in North America when, as an agent in London for several colonies, he spearheaded the repeal of the unpopular Stamp Act by the British Parliament.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] An accomplished diplomat, he was widely admired as the first U.S. ambassador to France and was a major figure in the development of positive Franco–American relations.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His efforts proved vital in securing French aid for the American Revolution.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] From 1785 to 1788, he served as President of Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] As a scientist, Franklin's studies of electricity made him a major figure in the American Enlightenment and the history of physics.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He also charted and named the Gulf Stream current.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His numerous important inventions include the lightning rod, bifocals, glass harmonica and the Franklin stove.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He founded many civic organizations, including the Library Company, the University of Pennsylvania, and Philadelphia's first fire department.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin earned the title of "The First American" for his early and indefatigable campaigning for colonial unity.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was the only person to sign the Declaration of Independence, the Treaty of Paris peace with Britain, and the Constitution.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Foundational in defining the American ethos, Franklin has been called "the most accomplished American of his age and the most influential in inventing the type of society America would become".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His more than 30,000 letters and documents have been collected in *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Anne Robert Jacques Turgot said of him: "Eripuit fulmen cœlo, mox sceptra tyrannis" ("He snatched lightning from the sky and the scepter from tyrants").
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin Franklin's father, Josiah Franklin, was a tallow chandler, soaper, and candlemaker.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Josiah Franklin was born at Ecton, Northamptonshire, England, on December 23, 1657, to Thomas Franklin and Jane White.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin's father and all four of his grandparents were born in England.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Josiah Franklin had a total of seventeen children with his two wives.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He married his first wife, Anne Child, in about 1677 in Ecton and emigrated with her to Boston in 1683; they had three children before emigration and four after.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Following her death, Josiah married Abiah Folger on July 9, 1689, in the Old South Meeting House by Reverend Samuel Willard, and had ten children with her.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin, their eighth child, was Josiah Franklin's fifteenth child overall, and his tenth and final son.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin Franklin's mother, Abiah, was born in Nantucket, Massachusetts Bay Colony, on August 15, 1667, to Peter Folger, a miller and schoolteacher, and his wife, Mary Morrell Folger, a former indentured servant.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Mary Folger came from a Puritan family that was among the first Pilgrims to flee to Massachusetts for religious freedom, sailing for Boston in 1635 after King Charles I of England had begun persecuting Puritans.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Her father Peter was "the sort of rebel destined to transform colonial America." As clerk of the court, he was arrested on February 10, 1676, and jailed on February 19 for his inability to pay bail.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He spent over a year and a half in jail.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was born on Milk Street in Boston, Province of Massachusetts Bay, on January 17, 1706, and baptized at the Old South Meeting House in Boston.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin's father wanted him to attend school with the clergy but only had enough money to send him to school for two years.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He attended Boston Latin School but did not graduate; he continued his education through voracious reading.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although "his parents talked of the church as a career" for Franklin, his schooling ended when he was ten.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He worked for his father for a time, and at 12 he became an apprentice to his brother James, a printer, who taught him the printing trade.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When Benjamin was 15, James founded *The New-England Courant*, which was the third newspaper founded in Boston.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When denied the chance to write a letter to the paper for publication, Franklin adopted the pseudonym of "Silence Dogood", a middle-aged widow.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Dogood's letters were published and became a subject of conversation around town.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Neither James nor the *Courant*'s readers were aware of the ruse, and James was unhappy with Benjamin when he discovered the popular correspondent was his younger brother.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was an advocate of free speech from an early age.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When his brother was jailed for three weeks in 1722 for publishing material unflattering to the governor, young Franklin took over the newspaper and had Mrs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Dogood proclaim, quoting *Cato's Letters*, "Without freedom of thought there can be no such thing as wisdom and no such thing as public liberty without freedom of speech." Franklin left his apprenticeship without his brother's permission, and in so doing became a fugitive.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] At age 17, Franklin ran away to Philadelphia, seeking a new start in a new city.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When he first arrived, he worked in several printing shops there, but he was not satisfied by the immediate prospects in any of these jobs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] After a few months, while Franklin was working in one printing house, Pennsylvania governor Sir William Keith convinced him to go to London, ostensibly to acquire the equipment necessary for establishing another newspaper in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Discovering that Keith's promises of backing a newspaper were empty, he worked as a typesetter in a printer's shop in what is today the Lady Chapel of Church of St Bartholomew-the-Great in the Smithfield area of London, which had at that time been deconsecrated.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He returned to Philadelphia in 1726 with the help of Thomas Denham, an English merchant who had emigrated but returned to England, and who employed Franklin as a clerk, shopkeeper, and bookkeeper in his business.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1727, at age 21, Franklin formed the Junto, a group of "like minded aspiring artisans and tradesmen who hoped to improve themselves while they improved their community." The Junto was a discussion group for issues of the day; it subsequently gave rise to many organizations in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Junto was modeled after English coffeehouses that Franklin knew well and which had become the center of the spread of Enlightenment ideas in Britain.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Reading was a great pastime of the Junto, but books were rare and expensive.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin conceived the idea of a subscription library, which would pool the funds of the members to buy books for all to read.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] This was the birth of the Library Company of Philadelphia, whose charter he composed in 1731.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Upon Denham's death, Franklin returned to his former trade.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1728, he set up a printing house in partnership with Hugh Meredith; the following year he became the publisher of *The Pennsylvania Gazette*, a newspaper in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The *Gazette* gave Franklin a forum for agitation about a variety of local reforms and initiatives through printed essays and observations.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Over time, his commentary, and his adroit cultivation of a positive image as an industrious and intellectual young man, earned him a great deal of social respect.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] But even after he achieved fame as a scientist and statesman, he habitually signed his letters with the unpretentious 'B.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1732, he published the first German-language newspaper in America – *Die Philadelphische Zeitung* – although it failed after only one year because four other newly founded German papers quickly dominated the newspaper market.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin also printed Moravian religious books in German.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He often visited Bethlehem, Pennsylvania, staying at the Moravian Sun Inn.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In a 1751 pamphlet on demographic growth and its implications for the Thirteen Colonies, he called the Pennsylvania Germans "Palatine Boors" who could never acquire the "Complexion" of Anglo-American settlers and referred to "Blacks and Tawneys" as weakening the social structure of the colonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although he apparently reconsidered shortly thereafter, and the phrases were omitted from all later printings of the pamphlet, his views may have played a role in his political defeat in 1764.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] According to Ralph Frasca, Franklin promoted the printing press as a device to instruct colonial Americans in moral virtue.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Frasca argues he saw this as a service to God, because he understood moral virtue in terms of actions, thus, doing good provides a service to God.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Despite his own moral lapses, Franklin saw himself as uniquely qualified to instruct Americans in morality.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He tried to influence American moral life through the construction of a printing network based on a chain of partnerships from the Carolinas to New England.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He thereby invented the first newspaper chain.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] It was more than a business venture, for like many publishers he believed that the press had a public-service duty.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When he established himself in Philadelphia, shortly before 1730, the town boasted two "wretched little" news sheets, Andrew Bradford's *The American Weekly Mercury* and Samuel Keimer's *Universal Instructor in all Arts and Sciences, and Pennsylvania Gazette*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] This instruction in all arts and sciences consisted of weekly extracts from *Chambers's Universal Dictionary*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin quickly did away with all of this when he took over the *Instructor* and made it *The Pennsylvania Gazette*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The *Gazette* soon became his characteristic organ, which he freely used for satire, for the play of his wit, even for sheer excess of mischief or of fun.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] From the first, he had a way of adapting his models to his own uses.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The series of essays called "The Busy-Body", which he wrote for Bradford's *American Mercury* in 1729, followed the general Addisonian form, already modified to suit homelier conditions.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The thrifty Patience, in her busy little shop, complaining of the useless visitors who waste her valuable time, is related to the women who address Mr.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Busy-Body himself is a true Censor Morum, as Isaac Bickerstaff had been in the *Tatler*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] And a number of the fictitious characters, Ridentius, Eugenius, Cato, and Cretico, represent traditional 18th-century classicism.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin even used this classical framework for contemporary satire, as seen in the character of Cretico, the "sour Philosopher", who is clearly a caricature of his rival, Samuel Keimer.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin had mixed success in his plan to establish an inter-colonial network of newspapers that would produce a profit for him and disseminate virtue.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Over the years he sponsored two dozen printers in Pennsylvania, South Carolina, New York, Connecticut, and even the Caribbean.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] By 1753, eight of the fifteen English language newspapers in the colonies were published by him or his partners.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He began in Charleston, South Carolina, in 1731.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his second editor died, the widow, Elizabeth Timothy, took over and made it a success.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] She was one of the colonial era's first woman printers.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] For three decades Franklin maintained a close business relationship with her and her son Peter Timothy, who took over the *South Carolina Gazette* in 1746.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The *Gazette* was impartial in political debates, while creating the opportunity for public debate, which encouraged others to challenge authority.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Timothy avoided blandness and crude bias and, after 1765, increasingly took a patriotic stand in the growing crisis with Great Britain.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin's *Connecticut Gazette* (1755–68), however, proved unsuccessful.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] As the Revolution approached, political strife slowly tore his network apart.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1730 or 1731, Franklin was initiated into the local Masonic lodge.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He became a grand master in 1734, indicating his rapid rise to prominence in Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The same year, he edited and published the first Masonic book in the Americas, a reprint of James Anderson's *Constitutions of the Free-Masons*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] John's Lodge in Philadelphia from 1735 to 1738.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In January 1738, "Franklin appeared as a witness" in a manslaughter trial against two men who killed "a simple-minded apprentice" named Daniel Rees in a fake Masonic initiation gone wrong.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] One of the men "threw, or accidentally spilled, the burning spirits, and Daniel Rees died of his burns two days later." While Franklin did not directly participate in the hazing that led to Rees's death, he knew of the hazing before it turned fatal, and did nothing to stop it.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was criticized for his inaction in *The American Weekly Mercury*, by his publishing rival Andrew Bradford.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin remained a Freemason for the rest of his life.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] At age 17 in 1723, Franklin proposed to 15-year-old Deborah Read while a boarder in the Read home.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] At that time, Deborah's mother was wary of allowing her young daughter to marry Franklin, who was on his way to London at Governor Keith's request, and also because of his financial instability.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Her own husband had recently died, and she declined Franklin's request to marry her daughter.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin travelled to London, and after he failed to communicate as expected with Deborah and her family, they interpreted his long silence as a breaking of his promises.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] At the urging of her mother, Deborah married a potter named John Rogers on August 5, 1725.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] John soon fled to Barbados with her dowry in order to avoid debts and prosecution.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Since Rogers's fate was unknown, bigamy laws prevented Deborah from remarrying.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin returned in 1726 and resumed his courtship of Deborah.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] They established a common-law marriage on September 1, 1730.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] They took in his recently acknowledged illegitimate young son and raised him in their household.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Their son, Francis Folger Franklin, was born in October 1732 and died of smallpox in 1736.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Their daughter, Sarah "Sally" Franklin, was born in 1743 and eventually married Richard Bache.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Deborah wrote to him in November 1769, saying she was ill due to "dissatisfied distress" from his prolonged absence, but he did not return until his business was done.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Deborah Read Franklin died of a stroke on December 14, 1774, while Franklin was on an extended mission to Great Britain; he returned in 1775.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1730, 24-year-old Franklin publicly acknowledged his illegitimate son William and raised him in his household.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] William was born on February 22, 1730, but his mother's identity is unknown.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was educated in Philadelphia and beginning at about age 30 studied law in London in the early 1760s.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] William himself fathered an illegitimate son, William Temple Franklin, born on the same day and month: February 22, 1760.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The boy's mother was never identified, and he was placed in foster care.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1762, the elder William Franklin married Elizabeth Downes, daughter of a planter from Barbados, in London.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1763, he was appointed as the last royal governor of New Jersey.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] A Loyalist to the king, William Franklin saw his relations with father Benjamin eventually break down over their differences about the American Revolutionary War, as Benjamin Franklin could never accept William's position.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Deposed in 1776 by the revolutionary government of New Jersey, William was placed under house arrest at his home in Perth Amboy for six months.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When finally released in a prisoner exchange in 1778, he moved to New York City, which was occupied by the British at the time.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] While in New York City, he became leader of the Board of Associated Loyalists, a quasi-military organization chartered by King George III and headquartered in New York City.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] They initiated guerrilla forays into New Jersey, southern Connecticut, and New York counties north of the city.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When British troops evacuated from New York, William Franklin left with them and sailed to England.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He settled in London, never to return to North America.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In the preliminary peace talks in 1782 with Britain, "...
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Benjamin Franklin insisted that loyalists who had borne arms against the United States would be excluded from this plea (that they be given a general pardon).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1732, Franklin began to publish the noted *Poor Richard's Almanack* (with content both original and borrowed) under the pseudonym Richard Saunders, on which much of his popular reputation is based.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The first issue published was for the upcoming year, 1733.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He had developed a distinct, signature style that was plain, pragmatic and had a sly, soft but self-deprecating tone with declarative sentences.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although it was no secret that he was the author, his Richard Saunders character repeatedly denied it.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] "Poor Richard's Proverbs", adages from this almanac, such as "A penny saved is twopence dear" (often misquoted as "A penny saved is a penny earned") and "Fish and visitors stink in three days", remain common quotations in the modern world.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Wisdom in folk society meant the ability to provide an apt adage for any occasion, and his readers became well prepared.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He sold about ten thousand copies per year—it became an institution.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1741, Franklin began publishing *The General Magazine and Historical Chronicle for all the British Plantations in America*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He used the heraldic badge of the Prince of Wales as the cover illustration.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin wrote a letter, "Advice to a Friend on Choosing a Mistress", dated June 25, 1745, in which he gives advice to a young man about channeling sexual urges.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Due to its licentious nature, it was not published in collections of his papers during the 19th century.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Federal court rulings from the mid-to-late 20th century cited the document as a reason for overturning obscenity laws and against censorship.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1736, Franklin created the Union Fire Company, one of the first volunteer firefighting companies in America.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In the same year, he printed a new currency for New Jersey based on innovative anti-counterfeiting techniques he had devised.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His political career also commenced, particularly as the Chief Clerk of the Pennsylvania Provincial Assembly, a capacity wherein he served until 1751.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Throughout his career, he was an advocate for paper money, publishing *A Modest Enquiry into the Nature and Necessity of a Paper Currency* in 1729, and his printer printed money.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was influential in the more restrained and thus successful monetary experiments in the Middle Colonies, which stopped deflation without causing excessive inflation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1766, he made a case for paper money to the British House of Commons.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] As he matured, Franklin began to concern himself more with public affairs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1743, he first devised a scheme for the Academy, Charity School, and College of Philadelphia; however, the person he had in mind to run the academy, Rev.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Richard Peters, refused and Franklin put his ideas away until 1749 when he printed his own pamphlet, *Proposals Relating to the Education of Youth in Pensilvania*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was appointed president of the Academy on November 13, 1749; the academy and the charity school opened in 1751.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1743, he founded the American Philosophical Society to help scientific men discuss their discoveries and theories.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He began the electrical research that, along with other scientific inquiries, would occupy him for the rest of his life, in between bouts of politics and moneymaking.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The largest of these was the "Association Battery" or "Grand Battery" of 50 guns.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1747, Franklin (already a very wealthy man) retired from printing and went into other businesses.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He formed a partnership with his foreman, David Hall, which provided Franklin with half of the shop's profits for 18 years.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] This lucrative business arrangement provided leisure time for study, and in a few years he had made many new discoveries.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin became involved in Philadelphia politics and rapidly progressed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In October 1748, he was selected as a councilman; in June 1749, he became a justice of the peace for Philadelphia; and in 1751, he was elected to the Pennsylvania Assembly.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] On August 10, 1753, he was appointed deputy postmaster-general of British North America.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His service in domestic politics included reforming the postal system, with mail sent out every week.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1751, Franklin and Thomas Bond obtained a charter from the Pennsylvania legislature to establish a hospital.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Pennsylvania Hospital was the first hospital in the colonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1752, Franklin organized the Philadelphia Contributionship, the Colonies' first homeowner's insurance company.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin solicited, printed in 1752, and promoted an American textbook of moral philosophy by Samuel Johnson, titled *Elementa Philosophica*, to be taught in the new colleges.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In June 1753, Johnson, Franklin, and Smith met in Stratford.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] They decided the new-model college would focus on the professions, with classes taught in English instead of Latin, have subject matter experts as professors instead of one tutor leading a class for four years, and there would be no religious test for admission.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Johnson went on to found King's College (now Columbia University) in New York City in 1754, while Franklin hired Smith as provost of the College of Philadelphia, which opened in 1755.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] At its first commencement, on May 17, 1757, seven men graduated; six with a Bachelor of Arts and one with a Master of Arts.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] It was later merged with the University of the State of Pennsylvania to become the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1754, he headed the Pennsylvania delegation to the Albany Congress.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] This meeting of several colonies had been requested by the Board of Trade in England to improve relations with the Indians and defense against the French.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin proposed a broad Plan of Union for the colonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] While the plan was not adopted, elements of it found their way into the Articles of Confederation and the Constitution.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1753, Harvard University and Yale awarded him honorary master of arts degrees.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1756, he was awarded an honorary Master of Arts degree from the College of William & Mary.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Later in 1756, Franklin organized the Pennsylvania Militia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He used Tun Tavern as a gathering place to recruit a regiment of soldiers to go into battle against the Native American uprisings that beset the American colonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Well known as a printer and publisher, Franklin was appointed postmaster of Philadelphia in 1737, holding the office until 1753, when he and publisher William Hunter were named deputy postmasters–general of British North America, the first to hold the office.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] (Joint appointments were standard at the time, for political reasons.) He was responsible for the British colonies from Pennsylvania north and east, as far as the island of Newfoundland.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] A post office for local and outgoing mail had been established in Halifax, Nova Scotia, by local stationer Benjamin Leigh, on April 23, 1754, but service was irregular.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin opened the first post office to offer regular, monthly mail in Halifax on December 9, 1755.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Meantime, Hunter became postal administrator in Williamsburg, Virginia, and oversaw areas south of Annapolis, Maryland.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin reorganized the service's accounting system and improved speed of delivery between Philadelphia, New York, and Boston.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] By 1761, efficiencies led to the first profits for the colonial post office.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When the lands of New France were ceded to the British under the Treaty of Paris in 1763, the British province of Quebec was created among them, and Franklin saw mail service expanded between Montreal, Trois-Rivières, Quebec City, and New York.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] For the greater part of his appointment, he lived in England (from 1757 to 1762, and again from 1764 to 1774)—about three-quarters of his term.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Eventually, his sympathies for the rebel cause in the American Revolution led to his dismissal on January 31, 1774.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] On July 26, 1775, the Second Continental Congress established the United States Post Office and named Franklin as the first United States postmaster general.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He had been a postmaster for decades and was a natural choice for the position.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He had just returned from England and was appointed chairman of a Committee of Investigation to establish a postal system.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The report of the committee, providing for the appointment of a postmaster general for the 13 American colonies, was considered by the Continental Congress on July 25 and 26.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] On July 26, 1775, Franklin was appointed postmaster general, the first appointed under the Continental Congress.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His apprentice, William Goddard, felt that his ideas were mostly responsible for shaping the postal system and that the appointment should have gone to him, but he graciously conceded it to Franklin, 36 years his senior.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin, however, appointed Goddard as Surveyor of the Posts, issued him a signed pass, and directed him to investigate and inspect the various post offices and mail routes as he saw fit.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The newly established postal system became the United States Post Office, a system that continues to operate today.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1757, he was sent to England by the Pennsylvania Assembly as a colonial agent to protest against the political influence of the Penn family, the proprietors of the colony.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He remained there for five years, striving to end the proprietors' prerogative to overturn legislation from the elected Assembly and their exemption from paying taxes on their land.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His lack of influential allies in Whitehall led to the failure of this mission.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] At this time, many members of the Pennsylvania Assembly were feuding with William Penn's heirs, who controlled the colony as proprietors.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his return to the colony, Franklin led the "anti-proprietary party" in the struggle against the Penn family and was elected Speaker of the Pennsylvania House in May 1764.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His call for a change from proprietary to royal government was a rare political miscalculation, however: Pennsylvanians worried that such a move would endanger their political and religious freedoms.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Because of these fears and because of political attacks on his character, Franklin lost his seat in the October 1764 Assembly elections.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The anti-proprietary party dispatched him to England again to continue the struggle against the Penn family proprietorship.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] During this trip, events drastically changed the nature of his mission.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In London, Franklin opposed the 1765 Stamp Act.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Unable to prevent its passage, he made another political miscalculation and recommended a friend, John Hughes, to the post of stamp distributor for Pennsylvania.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Pennsylvanians were outraged, believing that he had supported the measure all along, and threatened to destroy his home in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin soon learned of the extent of colonial resistance to the Stamp Act, and he testified during the House of Commons proceedings that led to its repeal.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] With this, Franklin suddenly emerged as the leading spokesman for American interests in England.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He wrote popular essays on behalf of the colonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Georgia, New Jersey, and Massachusetts also appointed him as their agent to the Crown.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] During his lengthy missions to London between 1757 and 1775, Franklin lodged in a house on Craven Street, just off the Strand in central London.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] During his stays there, he developed a close friendship with his landlady, Margaret Stevenson, and her circle of friends and relations, in particular, her daughter Mary, who was more often known as Polly.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The house is now a museum known as the Benjamin Franklin House.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Whilst in London, Franklin became involved in radical politics.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He belonged to a gentlemen's club (which he called "the honest Whigs"), which held stated meetings, and included members such as Richard Price, the minister of Newington Green Unitarian Church who ignited the Revolution controversy, and Andrew Kippis.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1756, Franklin had become a member of the Society for the Encouragement of Arts, Manufactures & Commerce (now the Royal Society of Arts), which had been founded in 1754.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his return to the United States in 1775, he became the Society's Corresponding Member, continuing a close connection.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Royal Society of Arts instituted a Benjamin Franklin Medal in 1956 to commemorate the 250th anniversary of his birth and the 200th anniversary of his membership of the RSA.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The study of natural philosophy (referred today as science in general) drew him into overlapping circles of acquaintance.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin was, for example, a corresponding member of the Lunar Society of Birmingham.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1759, the University of St Andrews awarded him an honorary doctorate in recognition of his accomplishments.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In October 1759, he was granted Freedom of the Borough of St Andrews.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was also awarded an honorary doctorate by Oxford University in 1762.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Because of these honors, he was often addressed as "Dr.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] While living in London in 1768, he developed a phonetic alphabet in *A Scheme for a new Alphabet and a Reformed Mode of Spelling*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] This reformed alphabet discarded six letters he regarded as redundant (c, j, q, w, x, and y), and substituted six new letters for sounds he felt lacked letters of their own.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] This alphabet never caught on, and he eventually lost interest.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] From the mid-1750s to the mid-1770s, Franklin returned to England and spent much of his time in London., using the city as a base from which to travel.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1771, he made short journeys through different parts of England, staying with Joseph Priestley at Leeds, Thomas Percival at Manchester and Erasmus Darwin at Lichfield.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In Scotland, he spent five days with Lord Kames near Stirling and stayed for three weeks with David Hume in Edinburgh.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In Ireland, he stayed with Lord Hillsborough.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He was the first American to receive this honor.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] While touring Ireland, he was deeply moved by the level of poverty he witnessed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The economy of the Kingdom of Ireland was affected by the same trade regulations and laws that governed the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin spent two months in German lands in 1766, but his connections to the country stretched across a lifetime.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He declared a debt of gratitude to German scientist Otto von Guericke for his early studies of electricity.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin also co-authored the first treaty of friendship between Prussia and America in 1785.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In September 1767, he visited Paris with his usual traveling partner, Sir John Pringle, 1st Baronet.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] News of his electrical discoveries was widespread in France.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His reputation meant that he was introduced to many influential scientists and politicians, and also to King Louis XV.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] One line of argument in Parliament was that Americans should pay a share of the costs of the French and Indian War and therefore taxes should be levied on them.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin became the American spokesman in highly publicized testimony in Parliament in 1766.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He stated that Americans already contributed heavily to the defense of the Empire.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He said local governments had raised, outfitted and paid 25,000 soldiers to fight France—as many as Great Britain itself sent—and spent many millions from American treasuries doing so in the French and Indian War alone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1772, Franklin obtained private letters of Thomas Hutchinson and Andrew Oliver, governor and lieutenant governor of the Province of Massachusetts Bay, proving that they had encouraged the Crown to crack down on Bostonians.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin sent them to North America, where they escalated tensions.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The letters were finally leaked to the public in the *Boston Gazette* in mid-June 1773, causing a political firestorm in Massachusetts and raising significant questions in England.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The British began to regard him as the fomenter of serious trouble.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Hopes for a peaceful solution ended as he was systematically ridiculed and humiliated by Solicitor-General Alexander Wedderburn, before the Privy Council on January 29, 1774.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He returned to Philadelphia in March 1775, and abandoned his accommodationist stance.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin is known to have occasionally attended the Hellfire Club's meetings during 1758 as a non-member during his time in England.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] However, some authors and historians would argue he was in fact a British spy.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] As there are no records left (having been burned in 1774), many of these members are just assumed or linked by letters sent to each other.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] One early proponent that Franklin was a member of the Hellfire Club and a double agent is the historian Donald McCormick, who has a history of making controversial claims.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1763, soon after Franklin returned to Pennsylvania from England for the first time, the western frontier was engulfed in a bitter war known as Pontiac's Rebellion.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Paxton Boys, a group of settlers convinced that the Pennsylvania government was not doing enough to protect them from American Indian raids, murdered a group of peaceful Susquehannock Indians and marched on Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin helped to organize a local militia to defend the capital against the mob.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He met with the Paxton leaders and persuaded them to disperse.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin wrote a scathing attack against the racial prejudice of the Paxton Boys.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He provided an early response to British surveillance through his own network of counter-surveillance and manipulation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] By the time Franklin arrived in Philadelphia on May 5, 1775, after his second mission to Great Britain, the American Revolution had begun at the Battles of Lexington and Concord the previous month, on April 19, 1775.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The New England militia had forced the main British army to remain inside Boston.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The Pennsylvania Assembly unanimously chose Franklin as their delegate to the Second Continental Congress.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In June 1776, he was appointed a member of the Committee of Five that drafted the Declaration of Independence.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Although he was temporarily disabled by gout and unable to attend most meetings of the committee, he made several "small but important" changes to the draft sent to him by Thomas Jefferson.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The "all hang together" saying ascribed to Franklin at the signing is probably apocryphal.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] On October 26, 1776, Franklin was dispatched to France as commissioner for the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He took with him as secretary his 16-year-old grandson, William Temple Franklin.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] They lived in a home in the Parisian suburb of Passy, donated by Jacques-Donatien Le Ray de Chaumont, who supported the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Among his associates in France was Honoré Gabriel Riqueti, comte de Mirabeau—a French Revolutionary writer, orator and statesman who in 1791 was elected president of the National Assembly.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In July 1784, Franklin met with Mirabeau and contributed anonymous materials that the Frenchman used in his first signed work: *Considerations sur l'ordre de Cincinnatus*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The publication was critical of the Society of the Cincinnati, established in the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin and Mirabeau thought of it as a "noble order", inconsistent with the egalitarian ideals of the new republic.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] During his stay in France, he was active as a Freemason, serving as venerable master of the lodge Les Neuf Sœurs from 1779 until 1781.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In 1784, when Franz Mesmer began to publicize his theory of "animal magnetism" which was considered offensive by many, Louis XVI appointed a commission to investigate it.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] These included the chemist Antoine Lavoisier, the physician Joseph-Ignace Guillotin, the astronomer Jean Sylvain Bailly, and Franklin.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin's advocacy for religious tolerance in France contributed to arguments made by French philosophers and politicians that resulted in Louis XVI's signing of the Edict of Versailles in November 1787.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] This edict effectively nullified the Edict of Fontainebleau, which had denied non-Catholics civil status and the right to openly practice their faith.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin also served as American minister to Sweden, although he never visited that country.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He negotiated a treaty that was signed in April 1783.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] On August 27, 1783, in Paris, he witnessed the world's first hydrogen balloon flight.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] *Le Globe*, created by professor Jacques Charles and Les Frères Robert, was watched by a vast crowd as it rose from the Champ de Mars (now the site of the Eiffel Tower).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin became so enthusiastic that he subscribed financially to the next project to build a manned hydrogen balloon.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] On December 1, 1783, Franklin was seated in the special enclosure for honored guests it took off from the Jardin des Tuileries, piloted by Charles and Nicolas-Louis Robert.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Walter Isaacson describes a chess game between Franklin and the Duchess of Bourbon, "who made a move that inadvertently exposed her king.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Ignoring the rules of the game, he promptly captured it.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] When he returned home in 1785, Franklin occupied a position second only to that of George Washington as the champion of American independence.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Le Ray honored him with a commissioned portrait painted by Joseph Duplessis, which now hangs in the National Portrait Gallery of the Smithsonian Institution in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] After his return, Franklin became an abolitionist and freed his two slaves.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He eventually became president of the Pennsylvania Abolition Society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Special balloting conducted October 18, 1785, unanimously elected him the sixth president of the Supreme Executive Council of Pennsylvania, replacing John Dickinson.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] The office was practically that of the governor.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He held that office for slightly over three years, longer than any other, and served the constitutional limit of three full terms.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Shortly after his initial election, he was re-elected to a full term on October 29, 1785, and again in the fall of 1786 and on October 31, 1787.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In that capacity, he served as host to the Constitutional Convention of 1787 in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] He also served as a delegate to the Convention.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] It was primarily an honorary position and he seldom engaged in debate.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] According to James McHenry, Elizabeth Willing Powel asked Franklin what kind of government they had wrought.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin suffered from obesity throughout his middle age and elder years, which resulted in multiple health problems, including gout, which worsened as he aged.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] In poor health during the signing of the U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Constitution in 1787, he was rarely seen in public after then until his death.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Franklin died from pleuritic attack at his home in Philadelphia on April 17, 1790, at age 84.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] His last reported words, conveyed to his daughter, were, "a dying man can do nothing easy", after she suggested that he change position in bed and lie on his side so he could breathe more easily.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Approximately 20,000 people attended Franklin's funeral, after which he was interred in Christ Church Burial Ground in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p01] Upon learning of his death, the Constitutional Assembly in Revolutionary France entered into a state of mourning for a period of three days, and memorial services were conducted in honor of Franklin throughout the country.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Among his many creations were the lightning rod, Franklin stove, bifocal glasses and the flexible urinary catheter.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was, along with his contemporary Leonhard Euler, the only major scientist who supported Christiaan Huygens's wave theory of light, which was basically ignored by the rest of the scientific community.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In the 18th century, Isaac Newton's corpuscular theory was held to be true; it took Thomas Young's well-known slit experiment in 1803 to persuade most scientists to believe Huygens's theory.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin started exploring the phenomenon of electricity in the 1740s, after he met the itinerant lecturer Archibald Spencer, who used static electricity in his demonstrations.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He proposed that "vitreous" and "resinous" electricity were not different types of "electrical fluid" (as electricity was called then), but the same "fluid" under different pressures.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1748, he constructed a multiple plate capacitor, that he called an "electrical battery" (not a true battery like Volta's pile) by placing eleven panes of glass sandwiched between lead plates, suspended with silk cords and connected by wires.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In pursuit of more pragmatic uses for electricity, remarking in spring 1749 that he felt "chagrin'd a little" that his experiments had heretofore resulted in "Nothing in this Way of Use to Mankind", Franklin planned a practical demonstration.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He proposed a dinner party where a turkey was to be killed via electric shock and roasted on an electrical spit.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin briefly investigated electrotherapy, including the use of the electric bath.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] This work led to the field becoming widely known.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In recognition of his work with electricity, he received the Royal Society's Copley Medal in 1753, and in 1756, he became one of the few 18th-century Americans elected a fellow of the Society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The CGS unit of electric charge has been named after him: one *franklin* (Fr) is equal to one statcoulomb.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin advised Harvard University in its acquisition of new electrical laboratory apparatus after the complete loss of its original collection, in a fire that destroyed the original Harvard Hall in 1764.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The collection he assembled later became part of the Harvard Collection of Historical Scientific Instruments, now on public display in its Science Center.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin published a proposal for an experiment to prove that lightning is electricity by flying a kite in a storm.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] On May 10, 1752, Thomas-François Dalibard of France conducted Franklin's experiment using a 40-foot-tall (12 m) iron rod instead of a kite, and he extracted electrical sparks from a cloud.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] On June 15, 1752, Franklin may possibly have conducted his well-known kite experiment in Philadelphia, successfully extracting sparks from a cloud.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He described the experiment in his newspaper, *The Pennsylvania Gazette*, on October 19, 1752, without mentioning that he himself had performed it.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] This account was read to the Royal Society on December 21 and printed as such in the *Philosophical Transactions*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Joseph Priestley published an account with additional details in his 1767 *History and Present Status of Electricity*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was careful to stand on an insulator, keeping dry under a roof to avoid the danger of electric shock.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Others, such as Georg Wilhelm Richmann in Russia, were indeed electrocuted in performing lightning experiments during the months immediately following his experiment.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his writings, Franklin indicates that he was aware of the dangers and offered alternative ways to demonstrate that lightning was electrical, as shown by his use of the concept of electrical ground.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He did not perform this experiment in the way that is often pictured in popular literature, flying the kite and waiting to be struck by lightning, as it would have been dangerous.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Instead he used the kite to collect some electric charge from a storm cloud, showing that lightning was electrical.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's electrical experiments led to his invention of the lightning rod.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Though Franklin is famously associated with kites from his lightning experiments, he has also been noted by many for using kites to pull humans and ships across waterways.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] George Pocock in the book *A Treatise on The Aeropleustic Art, or Navigation in the Air, by means of Kites, or Buoyant Sails* noted being inspired by Benjamin Franklin's traction of his body by kite power across a waterway.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin noted a principle of refrigeration by observing that on a very hot day, he stayed cooler in a wet shirt in a breeze than he did in a dry one.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] To understand this phenomenon more clearly, he conducted experiments.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1758 on a warm day in Cambridge, England, he and fellow scientist John Hadley experimented by continually wetting the ball of a mercury thermometer with ether and using bellows to evaporate the ether.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] With each subsequent evaporation, the thermometer read a lower temperature, eventually reaching 7 °F (−14 °C).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Another thermometer showed that the room temperature was constant at 65 °F (18 °C).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1761, Franklin wrote a letter to Mary Stevenson describing his experiments on the relationship between color and heat absorption.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He found that darker color clothes got hotter when exposed to sunlight than lighter color clothes, an early demonstration of black body thermal radiation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] One experiment he performed consisted of placing square pieces of cloth of various color out in the snow on a sunny day.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He waited some time and then measured that the black pieces sank furthest into the snow of all the colors, indicating that they got the hottest and melted the most snow.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] According to Michael Faraday, Franklin's experiments on the non-conduction of ice are worth mentioning, although the law of the general effect of liquefaction on electrolytes is not attributed to Franklin.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] However, as reported in 1836 by Franklin's great-grandson Alexander Dallas Bache of the University of Pennsylvania, the law of the effect of heat on the conduction of bodies otherwise non-conductors, for example, glass, could be attributed to Franklin.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] A certain quantity of heat will make some bodies good conductors, that will not otherwise conduct ..." and again, "...
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] As deputy postmaster, Franklin became interested in North Atlantic Ocean circulation patterns.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] While in England in 1768, he heard a complaint from the Colonial Board of Customs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] British packet ships carrying mail had taken several weeks longer to reach New York than it took an average merchant ship to reach Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The merchantmen had a longer and more complex voyage because they left from London, while the packets left from Falmouth in Cornwall.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin put the question to his cousin Timothy Folger, a Nantucket whaler captain, who told him that merchant ships routinely avoided a strong eastbound mid-ocean current.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The mail packet captains sailed dead into it, thus fighting an adverse current of 3 miles per hour (5 km/h).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin worked with Folger and other experienced ship captains, learning enough to chart the current and name it the Gulf Stream, by which it is still known today.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin published his Gulf Stream chart in 1770 in England, where it was ignored.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Subsequent versions were printed in France in 1778 and the U.S. in 1786.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The British original edition of the chart had been so thoroughly ignored that everyone assumed it was lost forever until Phil Richardson, a Woods Hole oceanographer and Gulf Stream expert, discovered it in the Bibliothèque Nationale in Paris in 1980.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] This find received front-page coverage in *The New York Times*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] It took many years for British sea captains to adopt Franklin's advice on navigating the current; once they did, they were able to trim two weeks from their sailing time.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] An aging Franklin accumulated all his oceanographic findings in *Maritime Observations*, published by the Philosophical Society's *transactions* in 1786.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] It contained ideas for sea anchors, catamaran hulls, watertight compartments, shipboard lightning rods and a soup bowl designed to stay stable in stormy weather.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] While traveling on a ship, Franklin had observed that the wake of a ship was diminished when the cooks scuttled their greasy water.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He studied the effects on a large pond in Clapham Common, London.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] On October 21, 1743, according to the popular myth, a storm moving from the southwest denied Franklin the opportunity of witnessing a lunar eclipse.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was said to have noted that the prevailing winds were actually from the northeast, contrary to what he had expected.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In correspondence with his brother, he learned that the same storm had not reached Boston until after the eclipse, despite the fact that Boston is to the northeast of Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He deduced that storms do not always travel in the direction of the prevailing wind, a concept that greatly influenced meteorology.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] After the Icelandic volcanic eruption of Laki in 1783, and the subsequent harsh European winter of 1784, Franklin made observations on the causal nature of these two seemingly separate events.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He wrote about them in a lecture series.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin had a major influence on the emerging science of demography or population studies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In the 1730s and 1740s, he began taking notes on population growth, finding that the American population had the fastest growth rate on Earth.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Emphasizing that population growth depended on food supplies, he emphasized the abundance of food and available farmland in America.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He calculated that America's population was doubling every 20 years and would surpass that of England in a century.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's predictions on how British mercantilism was unsustainable alarmed British leaders who did not want to be surpassed by the colonies, so they became more willing to impose restrictions on the colonial economy.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his capacity as a farmer, he wrote at least one critique about the negative consequences of price controls, trade restrictions, and subsidy of the poor.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Like the other advocates of republicanism, Franklin emphasized that the new republic could survive only if the people were virtuous.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] All his life, he explored the role of civic and personal virtue, as expressed in *Poor Richard's* aphorisms.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He felt that organized religion was necessary to keep men good to their fellow men, but rarely attended religious services himself.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's parents were both pious Puritans.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The family attended the Old South Church, the most liberal Puritan congregation in Boston, where Benjamin Franklin was baptized in 1706.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's father, a poor chandler, owned a copy of a book, *Bonifacius: Essays to Do Good*, by the Puritan preacher and family friend Cotton Mather, which Franklin often cited as a key influence on his life.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] "If I have been a useful citizen," Franklin wrote to Cotton Mather's son seventy years later, "the public owes the advantage of it to that book." His first pen name, Silence Dogood, paid homage both to the book and to a widely known sermon by Mather.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The book preached the importance of forming voluntary associations to benefit society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin learned about forming do-good associations from Mather, but his organizational skills made him the most influential force in making voluntarism an enduring part of the American ethos.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin formulated a presentation of his beliefs and published it in 1728.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He no longer accepted the key Puritan ideas regarding salvation, the divinity of Jesus, or indeed much religious dogma.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He classified himself as a deist in his 1771 autobiography, although he still considered himself a Christian.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He retained a strong faith in a God as the wellspring of morality and goodness in man, and as a Providential actor in history responsible for American independence.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The motion gained almost no support and was never brought to a vote.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was an enthusiastic admirer of the evangelical minister George Whitefield during the First Great Awakening.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He did not himself subscribe to Whitefield's theology, but he admired Whitefield for exhorting people to worship God through good works.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He published all of Whitefield's sermons and journals, thereby earning a lot of money and boosting the Great Awakening.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin retained a lifelong commitment to the non-religious Puritan virtues and political values he had grown up with, and through his civic work and publishing, he succeeded in passing these values into the American culture permanently.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He had a "passion for virtue." These Puritan values included his devotion to egalitarianism, education, industry, thrift, honesty, temperance, charity and community spirit.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The classical authors read in the Enlightenment period taught an abstract ideal of republican government based on hierarchical social orders of king, aristocracy and commoners.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] It was widely believed that English liberties relied on their balance of power, but also hierarchal deference to the privileged class.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin, steeped in Puritanism and an enthusiastic supporter of the evangelical movement, rejected the salvation dogma but embraced the radical notion of egalitarian democracy.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Max Weber considered Franklin's ethical writings a culmination of the Protestant ethic, which ethic created the social conditions necessary for the birth of capitalism.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] One of his characteristics was his respect, tolerance and promotion of all churches.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Ralph Frasca contends that in his later life he can be considered a non-denominational Christian, although he did not believe Christ was divine.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In a major scholarly study of his religion, Thomas Kidd argues that Franklin believed that true religiosity was a matter of personal morality and civic virtue.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The Church of England claimed him as one of them.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] On July 4, 1776, Congress appointed a three-member committee composed of Franklin, Jefferson, and Adams to design the Great Seal of the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's proposal (which was not adopted) featured the motto: "Rebellion to Tyrants is Obedience to God" and a scene from the Book of Exodus he took from the frontispiece of the Geneva Bible, with Moses, the Israelites, the pillar of fire, and George III depicted as pharaoh.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The design that was produced was not acted upon by Congress, and the Great Seal's design was not finalized until a third committee was appointed in 1782.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin sought to cultivate his character by a plan of 13 virtues, which he developed at age 20 (in 1726) and continued to practice in some form for the rest of his life.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Speak not but what may benefit others or yourself; avoid trifling conversation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Let all your things have their places; let each part of your business have its time.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Resolve to perform what you ought; perform without fail what you resolve.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Make no expense but to do good to others or yourself; i.e., waste nothing.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Lose no time; be always employ'd in something useful; cut off all unnecessary actions.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Use no hurtful deceit; think innocently and justly, and, if you speak, speak accordingly.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Wrong none by doing injuries, or omitting the benefits that are your duty.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Avoid extremes; forbear resenting injuries so much as you think they deserve.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Tolerate no uncleanliness in body, clothes, or habitation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Be not disturbed at trifles, or at accidents common or unavoidable.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Rarely use venery but for health or offspring, never to dullness, weakness, or the injury of your own or another's peace or reputation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin did not try to work on them all at once.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's views and practices concerning slavery evolved over the course of his life.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his early years, Franklin owned seven slaves, including two men who worked in his household and his shop, but in his later years became an adherent of abolition.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] A revenue stream for his newspaper was paid ads for the sale of slaves and for the capture of runaway slaves and Franklin allowed the sale of slaves in his general store.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He later became an outspoken critic of slavery.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1758, he advocated the opening of a school for the education of black slaves in Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He took two slaves to England with him, Peter and King.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] King escaped with a woman to live in the outskirts of London, and by 1758 he was working for a household in Suffolk.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] After returning from England in 1762, Franklin became more abolitionist in nature, attacking American slavery.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin refused to publicly debate the issue of slavery at the 1787 Constitutional Convention.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] At the time of the American founding, there were about half a million slaves in the United States, mostly in the five southernmost states, where they made up 40% of the population.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Many of the leading American founders – such as Thomas Jefferson, George Washington, and James Madison – owned slaves, but many others did not.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1790, Quakers from New York and Pennsylvania presented their petition for abolition to Congress.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Their argument against slavery was backed by the Pennsylvania Abolitionist Society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In his later years, as Congress was forced to deal with the issue of slavery, Franklin wrote several essays that stressed the importance of the abolition of slavery and of the integration of African Americans into American society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin became a vegetarian when he was a teenager apprenticing at a print shop, after coming upon a book by the early vegetarian advocate Thomas Tryon.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In addition, he would have also been familiar with the moral arguments espoused by prominent vegetarian Quakers in the colonial-era Province of Pennsylvania, including Benjamin Lay and John Woolman.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin also declared the consumption of fish to be "unprovoked murder." Despite his convictions, he began to eat fish after being tempted by fried cod on a boat sailing from Boston, justifying the eating of animals by observing that the fish's stomach contained other fish.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Nonetheless, he recognized the faulty ethics in this argument and would continue to be a vegetarian on and off.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was "excited" by tofu, which he learned of from the writings of a Spanish missionary to Southeast Asia, Domingo Fernández Navarrete.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's "Second Reply to *Vindex Patriae,*" a 1766 letter advocating self-sufficiency and less dependence on England, lists various examples of the bounty of American agricultural products, and does not mention meat.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The concept of preventing smallpox by variolation was introduced to colonial America by an African slave named Onesimus via his owner Cotton Mather in the early eighteenth century, but the procedure was not immediately accepted.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] James Franklin's newspaper carried articles in 1721 that vigorously denounced the concept.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] However, by 1736 Benjamin Franklin was known as a supporter of the procedure.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Therefore, when four-year-old "Franky" died of smallpox, opponents of the procedure circulated rumors that the child had been inoculated, and that this was the cause of his subsequent death.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] When Franklin became aware of this gossip, he placed a notice in the *Pennsylvania Gazette*, stating: "I do hereby sincerely declare, that he was not inoculated, but receiv'd the Distemper in the common Way of Infection ...
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] I intended to have my Child inoculated." The child had a bad case of flux diarrhea, and his parents had waited for him to get well before having him inoculated.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin wrote in his *Autobiography*: "In 1736 I lost one of my sons, a fine boy of four years old, by the small-pox, taken in the common way.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] I long regretted bitterly, and still regret that I had not given it to him by inoculation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In a letter to Joseph Priestley, dated February 8, 1780, Franklin speculated that in the future "all Diseases may by sure means be prevented or cured, not excepting even that of Old Age, and our Lives lengthened at pleasure even beyond the antediluvian Standard".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin is known to have played the violin, the harp, and the guitar.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He also composed music, which included a string quartet in early classical style.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] While he was in London, he developed a much-improved version of the glass harmonica, in which the glasses rotate on a shaft, with the player's fingers held steady, instead of the other way around.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He worked with the London glassblower Charles James to create it, and instruments based on his mechanical version soon found their way to other parts of Europe.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Joseph Haydn, a fan of Franklin's enlightened ideas, had a glass harmonica in his instrument collection.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart composed for Franklin's glass harmonica, as did Ludwig van Beethoven.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Gaetano Donizetti used the instrument in the accompaniment to Amelia's aria "Par che mi dica ancora" in the tragic opera *Il castello di Kenilworth* (1821), as did Camille Saint-Saëns in his 1886 *The Carnival of the Animals*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Richard Strauss calls for the glass harmonica in his 1917 *Die Frau ohne Schatten*, and numerous other composers used Franklin's instrument as well.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was playing chess by around 1733, making him the first chess player known by name in the American colonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] His essay on "The Morals of Chess" in *Columbian Magazine* in December 1786 is the second known writing on chess in America.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] This essay in praise of chess and prescribing a code of behavior for the game has been widely reprinted and translated.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He and a friend used chess as a means of learning the Italian language, which both were studying; the winner of each game between them had the right to assign a task, such as parts of the Italian grammar to be learned by heart, to be performed by the loser before their next meeting.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin was able to play chess more frequently against stronger opposition during his many years as a civil servant and diplomat in England, where the game was far better established than in America.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He was able to improve his playing standard by facing more experienced players during this period.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He regularly attended Old Slaughter's Coffee House in London for chess and socializing, making many important personal contacts.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] While in Paris, both as a visitor and later as ambassador, he visited the famous Café de la Régence, which France's strongest players made their regular meeting place.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] No records of his games have survived, so it is not possible to ascertain his playing strength in modern terms.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The Franklin Mercantile Chess Club in Philadelphia, the second oldest chess club in the U.S., is named in his honor.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin bequeathed £1,000 (about $4,400 at the time, or about $125,000 in 2021 dollars) each to the cities of Boston and Philadelphia, in trust to gather interest for 200 years.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The trust began in 1785 when the French mathematician Charles-Joseph Mathon de la Cour, who admired Franklin greatly, wrote a friendly parody of Franklin's *Poor Richard's Almanack* called *Fortunate Richard*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The main character leaves a smallish amount of money in his will, five lots of 100 *livres*, to collect interest over one, two, three, four or five full centuries, with the resulting astronomical sums to be spent on impossibly elaborate utopian projects.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin, who was 79 years old at the time, wrote thanking him for a great idea and telling him that he had decided to leave a bequest of 1,000 pounds each to his native Boston and his adopted Philadelphia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] By 1990, more than $2,000,000 (~$4.23 million in 2024) had accumulated in Franklin's Philadelphia trust, which had loaned the money to local residents.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] From 1940 to 1990, the money was used mostly for mortgage loans.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] When the trust came due, Philadelphia decided to spend it on scholarships for local high school students.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin's Boston trust fund accumulated almost $5,000,000 during that same time; at the end of its first 100 years a portion was allocated to help establish a trade school that became the Franklin Institute of Boston, and the entire fund was later dedicated to supporting this institute.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1787, a group of prominent ministers in Lancaster, Pennsylvania, proposed the foundation of a new college named in Franklin's honor.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin donated £200 towards the development of Franklin College (now called Franklin & Marshall College).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] As the only person to have signed the Declaration of Independence in 1776, Treaty of Alliance with France in 1778, Treaty of Paris in 1783, and U.S.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Constitution in 1787, Franklin is considered one of the leading Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Since 1914, it has adorned American $100 bills.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] From 1948 to 1963, Franklin's portrait was on the half-dollar.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He has appeared on a $50 bill and on several varieties of the $100 bill from 1914 and 1918.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Franklin also appears on the $1,000 Series EE savings bond.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] On April 12, 1976, as part of a bicentennial celebration, Congress dedicated a 20-foot (6 m) tall marble statue in Philadelphia's Franklin Institute as the Benjamin Franklin National Memorial.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Vice President Nelson Rockefeller presided over the dedication ceremony.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Many of Franklin's personal possessions are on display at the institute.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In London, his house at 36 Craven Street, which is the only surviving former residence of Franklin, was first marked with a blue plaque and has since been opened to the public as the Benjamin Franklin House.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] In 1998, workmen restoring the building dug up the remains of six children and four adults hidden below the home.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] A total of 15 bodies have been recovered.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The Friends of Benjamin Franklin House (the organization responsible for the restoration) note that the bones were likely placed there by William Hewson, who lived in the house for two years and who had built a small anatomy school at the back of the house.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] They note that while Franklin likely knew what Hewson was doing, he probably did not participate in any dissections because he was much more of a physicist than a medical man.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He has been honored on U.S. postage stamps many times.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] The image of Franklin, the first postmaster general of the United States, occurs on the face of U.S. postage more than any other American save that of George Washington.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] He appeared on the first U.S. postage stamp issued in 1847.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Post Office issued a series of postage stamps commonly referred to as the Washington–Franklin Issues, in which Washington and Franklin were depicted many times over a 14-year period, the longest run of any one series in U.S. postal history.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] However, he only appears on a few commemorative stamps.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/benjamin-franklin-p02] Some of the finest portrayals of Franklin on record can be found on the engravings inscribed on the face of U.S. postage.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Arnold was born in Casnovia, Michigan on August 14, 1861.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] After graduating from Hillsdale College in Michigan and the University of Nebraska in 1897, Arnold set up his own company in Chicago at a time when railroads were converting their power sources from steam to electricity.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] In 1898, Arnold developed a new method of converting alternating current from power plants to direct current in substations for the Chicago & Milwaukee Electric Railway.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] This innovative electrification system would eventually become a standard in the interurban and street railway industries.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Between 1898 and 1912, he assisted the New York Central Railroad and the Hudson River Railroad in conversion of their lines leading into Grand Central Terminal.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] When the Interborough Rapid Transit's first line opened in 1904, the subway proved to be more popular than envisioned.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] By 1908, a system designed for a maximum of 600,000 passengers per day was being used by 800,000.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Arnold was called upon again to solve the problem.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] His solution was to place automatic speed control devices on the trains themselves, so that more trains could be run during each hour.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Arnold also assisted in the conversion of electrified railways in Los Angeles and Pittsburgh, and the cable car systems in San Francisco.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Arnold was president of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers from 1903 to 1904.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] On December 14, 1917, Arnold transferred to the regular Army as a lieutenant colonel in the Aviation Section of the Signal Corps.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] He was assigned to aircraft equipment production in Washington, DC.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] He was a colonel in the inactive reserve after 1929.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Arnold died at his home in Chicago on January 29, 1942, and is buried in Ashland Cemetery, in his hometown of Ashland, Nebraska.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] *Martin, Thomas Commerford (September 9, 1911).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] "Bion Joseph Arnold An Engineer Who Is the Right-hand Man of Public Service Commissions".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] *Before the North Shore Line: The Early Years 1894-1916*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Chicago, Illinois: Central Electric Railfans Association. p.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/bion-j-arnold] Clifton Hood, "The Impact of the IRT on New York City", Historical American Engineering Record survey number HAER NY-122, pp.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] (Please, see an overview of this ISO/IEC JTC 1 and IEEE standardization effort in the article published by Stephen B.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] Seidman, CSDP. ) The standard was formulated in such a way, that it allowed to recognize the CSDP certification scheme as basically aligned with it, soon after the standard's release date, 2008-09-01.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] Several later revisions of the CSDP certification were undertaken with the aim of making the alignment more complete.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] The certification was initially offered by the IEEE Computer Society to experienced software engineering and software development practitioners globally in 2001 in the course of the certification examination beta-testing.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] The CSDP certification program has been officially approved in 2002.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] After December 2014 this certification program has been discontinued, all issued certificates are recognized as valid forever.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] A number of new similar certifications were introduced by the IEEE Computer Society, including the *Professional Software Engineering Master (PSEM)* and *Professional Software Engineering Process Master (PSEPM)* Certifications (the later soon discontinued).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] The CSDP examination tested candidates' proficiency in internationally accepted, industry-standard software engineering principles and practices.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] CSDP credential holders are also obligated to adhere to the IEEE/ACM's Software Engineering Code of Ethics and Professional Practice.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] As of 2021, the IEEE-CS offer which is a successor to CSDP is the **Professional Software Engineering Master (PSEM)** certification.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] (There is also the **Professional Software Developer (PSD)** certification, which covers only 4 knowledge areas: software requirements, software design, software construction, and software testing.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] Candidates had to undergo a peer review of their education and professional qualifications in order to receive authorization to take the CSDP examination.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] Candidates therefore had to submit an application to the IEEE Computer Society that provided verifiable information regarding their educational background and professional experience.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] The **Certified Software Development Associate (CSDA)** certification was available to graduating students and early-career software professionals who did not meet the eligibility requirements for the CSDP.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] The CSDP examination content was based on the *Guide To The Software Engineering Body of Knowledge*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] The examination covered content from all primary knowledge areas in the SWEBOK Guide Version 3.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/certified-software-development-professional] Below is a list of the topics tested in terms of their proportion of the total examination.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] At the time of his death, Steinmetz held over 200 patents.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A genius in both mathematics and electronics, he did work that earned him the nicknames "Forger of Thunderbolts" and "The Wizard of Schenectady".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was born Karl August Rudolph Steinmetz on April 9, 1865, in Breslau, Province of Silesia, Prussia (now Wrocław, Poland), the son of Caroline (Neubert) and Karl Heinrich Steinmetz.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was baptized as a Lutheran into the Evangelical Church of Prussia.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz, who stood only 4 ft 0 in (1.22 m) tall as an adult, had dwarfism, hunchback, and hip dysplasia, as did his father and grandfather.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz graduated with honors from St.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Following Gymnasium, Steinmetz studied at the University of Breslau to begin work on his undergraduate degree in 1883.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Nearing completion of his doctorate in 1888, he was forced to flee to Zurich, Switzerland, as the German government was preparing to prosecute him for his socialist activities.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] As socialist meetings and press had been banned in Germany, Steinmetz fled to Zurich in 1889 to escape possible arrest.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Faced with an expiring visa, he emigrated to the United States in 1889 at the age of 24.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He changed his first name to "Charles" to sound more American, and chose the middle name "Proteus", a wise hunchbacked character from the *Odyssey* who knew many secrets, after an epithet bestowed upon him by his college fraternity brothers.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was politically active in the US as a technocratic socialist for over thirty years.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Following the Bolshevik introduction of a technocratic plan to electrify Russia, Steinmetz spoke of Lenin alongside Albert Einstein as the "two greatest minds of our time." He believed in a corporatist industrial government also covering its human welfare function.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A member of the original Technical Alliance, which also included Thorstein Veblen and Leland Olds, Steinmetz had great faith in the ability of machines to eliminate human toil and create abundance for all.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He put it this way: "Some day we [will] make the good things of life for everybody." Steinmetz's techno-utopian optimism was deeply intertwined with his political beliefs, and he was convinced that the spread of electrification would inevitably steer human society toward socialism.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz is known for his contribution in three major fields of alternating current (AC) systems theory: hysteresis, steady-state analysis, and transients.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Shortly after arriving in the United States, Steinmetz went to work for Rudolf Eickemeyer in Yonkers, New York, and published in the field of magnetic hysteresis, earning worldwide professional recognition.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Eickemeyer's firm developed transformers for use in the transmission of electrical power among many other mechanical and electrical devices.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1893 Eickemeyer's company, along with all of its patents and designs, was bought by the newly formed General Electric Company, where Steinmetz quickly became known as the engineering wizard in GE's engineering community.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's work revolutionized AC circuit theory and analysis, which had been carried out using complicated, time-consuming calculus-based methods.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In the groundbreaking paper, "Complex Quantities and Their Use in Electrical Engineering", presented at a July 1893 meeting published in the American Institute of Electrical Engineers (AIEE), Steinmetz simplified these complicated methods to "a simple problem of algebra".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He systematized the use of complex number phasor representation in electrical engineering education texts, whereby the lower-case letter "j" is used to designate the 90-degree rotation operator in AC system analysis.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] His seminal books and many other AIEE papers "taught a whole generation of engineers how to deal with AC phenomena".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz also greatly advanced the understanding of lightning.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] His systematic experiments resulted in the first laboratory-created "man-made lightning", earning him the nickname "Forger of Thunderbolts".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] These were conducted in a football-field-sized laboratory at General Electric, using 120 000-volt generators.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Like alternating-current pioneer Nikola Tesla, he also erected a lightning tower to attract natural lightning to study its patterns and effects, which resulted in several theories.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was granted an honorary degree from Harvard University in 1901 and a doctorate from Union College in 1903.; other awards include the Certificate of Merit of Franklin Institute, 1908; the Elliott Cresson Medal, 1913; and the Cedergren Medal, 1914.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was also an elected member of both the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the American Philosophical Society.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz wrote 13 books and 60 articles, not exclusively about engineering.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He was a member and adviser to the fraternity Phi Gamma Delta at Union College, whose chapter house was one of the first electrified residences.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] While serving as president of the Schenectady Board of Education, Steinmetz introduced numerous progressive reforms, including extended school hours, school meals, school nurses, special classes for the children of immigrants, and the distribution of free textbooks.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz had dwarfism, standing only 4 ft 0 in (1.22 m) tall as an adult, and was affected by kyphosis like his father and grandfather.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In spite of his love for children and family life, Steinmetz remained unmarried, to prevent his spinal deformity from being passed to any offspring.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] When Joseph LeRoy Hayden, a loyal and hardworking lab assistant, announced that he would marry and look for his own living quarters, Steinmetz made the unusual proposal of opening his large home, complete with research lab, greenhouse, and office to the Haydens and their prospective family.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Hayden favored the idea, but his future wife was wary of the unorthodox arrangement.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] She agreed after Steinmetz's assurance that she could run the house as she saw fit.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] After an uneasy start, the arrangement worked well for all parties, especially after three Hayden children were born.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz legally adopted Joseph Hayden as his son, becoming grandfather to the youngsters, entertaining them with fantastic stories and spectacular scientific demonstrations.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] The unusual, harmonious living arrangement lasted for the rest of Steinmetz's life.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1894, Steinmetz founded the *Mohawk Aerial Navigation Company (Ltd.)*, which became the first practical, active gliding club in the world.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He died on October 26, 1923, at the age of 58 and was buried in Vale Cemetery in Schenectady.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz earned wide recognition among the scientific community and numerous awards and honors both during his life and posthumously.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's equation, derived from his experiments, defines the approximate heat energy due to magnetic hysteresis released, per cycle per unit volume of magnetic material.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A Steinmetz solid is the solid body generated by the intersection of two or three cylinders of equal radius at right angles.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's equivalent circuit is still widely used for the design and testing of induction machines.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] One of the highest technical recognitions given by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, the "IEEE Charles Proteus Steinmetz Award", is given for major contributions to standardization within the field of electrical and electronics engineering.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Memorial Lecture series was begun in his honor in 1925, sponsored by the Schenectady branch of the IEEE.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Through 2017 seventy-three gatherings have taken place, held almost exclusively at Union College, featuring notable figures such as Nobel laureate experimental physicist Robert A.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Millikan, helicopter inventor Igor Sikorsky, nuclear submarine pioneer Admiral Hyman G.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Rickover (1963), Nobel-winning semiconductor inventor William Shockley, and Internet "founding father" Leonard Kleinrock.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz's connection to Union is further celebrated with the annual Steinmetz Symposium, a day-long event in which Union undergraduates give presentations on research they have done.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Hall, which houses the Union College computer center, is named after him.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Scholarship is awarded annually by the college, underwritten since its inception in 1923 by the General Electric Company.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz Memorial Scholarship was later established at Union by Marjorie Hayden, daughter of Joseph and Corrine Hayden, and is awarded to students majoring in engineering or physics.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A 1914 "Duplex Drive Brougham" Detroit Electric automobile that once belonged to Steinmetz was purchased by Union College in 1971, and restored for use in campus ceremonies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] The Steinmetz car is permanently displayed in the first-floor corridor between the Wold Center and F.W.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A Chicago public high school, Steinmetz College Prep, is named for him, as well as a Schenectady public school, the Steinmetz Career and Leadership Academy, formerly Steinmetz Middle-School.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A public park in north Schenectady, New York, was named for him in 1931.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In 1983, the US Post Office included Steinmetz in a series of postage stamps commemorating American inventors.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In May 2015, a life-size bronze statue of Charles Steinmetz meeting Thomas Edison by sculptor and caster Dexter Benedict was unveiled on a plaza on the corner of Erie Boulevards and South Ferry Street in Schenectady.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Charles Steinmetz's Mohawk River cabin is preserved and on display in the outdoor collection of historic structures in Greenfield Village, part of the Henry Ford Museum complex in Dearborn, Michigan.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz is featured in John Dos Passos's *U.S.A.* trilogy in one of the biographies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] He also serves as a major character in Starling Lawrence's 2006 book, *The Lightning Keeper*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz is a major character in the novel *Electric City* by Elizabeth Rosner.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] In the 1944 Three Stooges short "Busy Buddies", Moe Howard references Steinmetz.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] Steinmetz was portrayed in 1959 by the actor Rod Steiger in the CBS television anthology series, *The Joseph Cotten Show*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] The episode focused on his socialist activities in Germany.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A famous anecdote about Steinmetz concerns a troubleshooting consultation at Henry Ford's River Rouge Plant.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/charles-proteus-steinmetz] A humorous aspect of the story is the "itemized bill" he submitted for the work performed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago was incorporated as a city in 1837 near a portage between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River watershed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] It grew rapidly in the mid-19th century.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed several square miles and left more than 100,000 homeless, but Chicago's population continued to grow.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago made noted contributions to urban planning and architecture, such as the Chicago School, the development of the City Beautiful movement, and the steel-framed skyscraper.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago is an international hub for finance, culture, commerce, industry, education, technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] It has the largest and most diverse finance derivatives market in the world, generating 20% of all volume in commodities and financial futures alone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] O'Hare International Airport is routinely ranked among the world's top ten busiest airports by passenger traffic, and the region is also the nation's railroad hub.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Chicago area has one of the highest gross domestic products (GDP) of any urban region in the world, ranking sixth globally, generating over $919 billion in 2024.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago's economy is diverse, with no single industry employing more than 14% of the workforce.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago is a major destination for tourism, with nearly 57 million people visiting its cultural institutions, Lake Michigan beaches, restaurants, and other tourist sites in 2025.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago's culture has made significant contributions to the visual arts, literature, film, theater, comedy (especially improvisational comedy), food, dance, and music (particularly jazz, blues, soul, hip-hop, gospel, industrial, and electronic dance music, especially house music).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago is home to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and the Lyric Opera of Chicago, while the Art Institute of Chicago has an influential visual arts museum and art school.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Chicago area is home to the University of Chicago, Northwestern University, and the University of Illinois Chicago, among other institutions of higher education.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] It also hosts the Barack Obama Presidential Center.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Professional sports in Chicago include all major professional leagues, including two Major League Baseball teams.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city also hosts the Chicago Marathon, one of the World Marathon Majors.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The name *Chicago* is derived from a French rendering of the indigenous Miami–Illinois word *šikaakwa*, which was a name for a wild relative of onion and garlic known to modern botanists as *Allium tricoccum*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The first known reference to the site of the city of Chicago as "*Checagou*" was by Robert de La Salle around 1679 in a memoir.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Henri Joutel, in his journal of 1688, noted that the eponymous wild "garlic" grew profusely in the area.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city has had several nicknames throughout its history, such as the Windy City, Chi-Town, Second City, and City of the Big Shoulders.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In the mid-18th century, the area was inhabited by the Potawatomi, an indigenous tribe who had succeeded the Miami, Sauk and Meskwaki peoples in this region.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The first known permanent settler in Chicago was a trader, Jean Baptiste Point du Sable.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Du Sable was of African descent, perhaps born in the French colony of Saint-Domingue (Haiti), and he established the settlement in the 1780s.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] He is commonly known as the "Founder of Chicago".
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1795, following the victory of the new United States in the Northwest Indian War, an area that was to be part of Chicago was turned over to the U.S. for a military post by native tribes in accordance with the Treaty of Greenville.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Army constructed Fort Dearborn, which was destroyed during the War of 1812 in the Battle of Fort Dearborn by the Potawatomi before being later rebuilt.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] After the War of 1812, the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi tribes ceded additional land to the United States in the 1816 Treaty of St.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Potawatomi were forcibly removed from their land after the 1833 Treaty of Chicago and sent west of the Mississippi River as part of the federal policy of Indian removal.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] On August 12, 1833, the Town of Chicago was organized with a population of about 200.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Within seven years it grew to more than 6,000 people.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] On June 15, 1835, the first public land sales began with Edmund Dick Taylor as Receiver of Public Monies.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The City of Chicago was incorporated on Saturday, March 4, 1837, and for several decades was the world's fastest-growing city.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] As the site of the Chicago Portage, the city became an important transportation hub between the eastern and western United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago's first railway, Galena and Chicago Union Railroad, and the Illinois and Michigan Canal opened in 1848.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The canal allowed steamboats and sailing ships on the Great Lakes to connect to the Mississippi River.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] A flourishing economy brought residents from rural communities and immigrants from abroad.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Manufacturing and retail and finance sectors became dominant, influencing the American economy.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Chicago Board of Trade (established 1848) listed the first-ever standardized "exchange-traded" forward contracts, which were called futures contracts.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In the 1850s, Chicago gained national political prominence as the home of Senator Stephen Douglas, the champion of the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the "popular sovereignty" approach to the issue of the spread of slavery.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] These issues also helped propel another Illinoisan, Abraham Lincoln, to the national stage.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Lincoln was nominated in Chicago for U.S. president at the 1860 Republican National Convention, which was held in a purpose-built auditorium called the Wigwam.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] He defeated Douglas in the general election, and this set the stage for the American Civil War.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] To accommodate rapid population growth and demand for better sanitation, the city improved its infrastructure.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In February 1856, Chicago's Common Council approved Chesbrough's plan to build the United States' first comprehensive sewerage system.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The project raised much of central Chicago to a new grade with the use of jackscrews for raising buildings.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] While elevating Chicago, and at first improving the city's health, the untreated sewage and industrial waste now flowed into the Chicago River, and subsequently into Lake Michigan, polluting the city's primary freshwater source.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city responded by tunneling two miles (3.2 km) out into Lake Michigan to newly built water cribs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1900, the problem of sewage contamination was largely resolved when the city completed a major engineering feat.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] It reversed the flow of the Chicago River so that the water flowed away from Lake Michigan rather than into it.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] This project began with the construction and improvement of the Illinois and Michigan Canal, and was completed with the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal that connects to the Illinois River, which flows into the Mississippi River.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] On October 8, 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6.4 km) long and 1-mile (1.6 km) wide, a large section of the city at the time.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] At least 300 people were killed and over 100,000 were left homeless from the fire.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] However, much of the city, including railroads and stockyards, survived intact, and from the ruins of the previous wooden structures arose more modern constructions of steel and stone.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] These set a precedent for worldwide construction.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] During its rebuilding period, Chicago constructed the world's first skyscraper in 1885, using steel-skeleton construction.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Labor conflicts followed the industrial boom and the rapid expansion of the labor pool during the Gilded Age, including the Haymarket affair on May 4, 1886, and in 1894 the Pullman Strike.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Anarchist and socialist groups played prominent roles in creating very large and highly organized labor actions.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Concern for social problems among Chicago's immigrant poor led Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr to found Hull House in 1889.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Programs that were developed there became a model for the new field of social work.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] During the 1870s and 1880s, Chicago attained national stature as the leader in the movement to improve public health.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] City laws and later, state laws that upgraded standards for the medical profession and fought urban epidemics of cholera, smallpox, and yellow fever were both passed and enforced.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] These laws became templates for public health reform in other cities and states.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city established many large, well-landscaped municipal parks, which also included public sanitation facilities.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The chief advocate for improving public health in Chicago was John H.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Rauch established a plan for Chicago's park system in 1866.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] He created Lincoln Park by closing a cemetery filled with shallow graves, and in 1867, in response to an outbreak of cholera he helped establish a new Chicago Board of Health.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Ten years later, he became the secretary and then the president of the first Illinois State Board of Health, which carried out most of its activities in Chicago.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In the 1800s, Chicago became the nation's railroad hub, and by 1910 over 20 railroads operated passenger service out of six different downtown terminals.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1883, Chicago's railway managers needed a general time convention, so they developed the standardized system of North American time zones.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] This system for telling time spread throughout the continent.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The desire to join the city was driven by municipal services that the city could provide its residents.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1893, Chicago hosted the World's Columbian Exposition on former marshland at the present location of Jackson Park.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Exposition drew 27.5 million visitors, and is considered the most influential world's fair in history.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city's municipal device, a Y within a circle, was the result of a contest run by the *Chicago Tribune* in 1892, in anticipation of the Columbian Exposition.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The University of Chicago, formerly at another location, moved to the same South Side location in 1892.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The term "midway" for a fair or carnival referred originally to the Midway Plaisance, a strip of park land that still runs through the University of Chicago campus and connects the Washington and Jackson Parks.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago's flourishing economy attracted huge numbers of new immigrants from Europe and migrants from the Eastern United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Of the total population in 1900, more than 77% were either foreign-born or born in the United States of foreign parentage.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Germans, Irish, Poles, Swedes, and Czechs made up nearly two-thirds of the foreign-born population (by 1900, whites were 98.1% of the city's population).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] During World War I and the 1920s there was a major expansion in industry.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the Southern United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Between 1910 and 1930, the African American population of Chicago increased dramatically, from 44,103 to 233,903.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] This Great Migration had an immense cultural impact, called the Chicago Black Renaissance, part of the New Negro Movement, in art, literature, and music.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Continuing racial tensions and violence in the city, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919, also occurred.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The ratification of the 18th amendment to the Constitution in 1919 made the production and sale (including exportation) of alcoholic beverages illegal in the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] This ushered in the beginning of what is known as the gangster era, a time that roughly spans from 1919 until 1933 when Prohibition was repealed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The 1920s saw gangsters, including Al Capone, Dion O'Banion, Bugs Moran and Tony Accardo battle law enforcement and each other on the streets of Chicago during the Prohibition era.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago was the location of the infamous St.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Valentine's Day Massacre in 1929, when Al Capone sent men to gun down members of a rival gang, North Side, led by Bugs Moran, leaving seven rival members dead.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] From 1920 to 1921, the city was affected by a series of tenant rent strikes, which led to the formation of the Chicago Tenants Protective association, passage of the Kessenger tenant laws, and of a heat ordinance that legally required flats to be kept above 68 °F during winter months by landlords.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago was the first American city to have a homosexual-rights organization.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The organization, formed in 1924, was called the Society for Human Rights.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] It produced the first American publication for homosexuals, *Friendship and Freedom*.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Police and political pressure caused the organization to disband.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Great Depression brought unprecedented suffering to Chicago, in no small part due to the city's heavy reliance on heavy industry.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Notably, industrial areas on the south side and neighborhoods lining both branches of the Chicago River were devastated; by 1933 over 50% of industrial jobs in the city had been lost, and unemployment rates amongst blacks and Latinos in the city were over 40%.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Republican political machine in Chicago was utterly destroyed by the economic crisis, and every mayor since 1931 has been a Democrat.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] From 1928 to 1933, the city witnessed a tax revolt, and the city was unable to meet payroll or provide relief efforts.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The fiscal crisis was resolved by 1933, and at the same time, federal relief funding began to flow into Chicago.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago was also a hotbed of labor activism, with Unemployed Councils contributing heavily in the early depression to create solidarity for the poor and demand relief; these organizations were created by socialist and communist groups.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] By 1935, the Workers Alliance of America began organizing the poor, workers, the unemployed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In the spring of 1937 Republic Steel Works witnessed the Memorial Day massacre of 1937 in the neighborhood of East Side.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1933, Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak was fatally wounded in Miami, Florida, during a failed assassination attempt on President-elect Franklin D.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1933 and 1934, the city celebrated its centennial by hosting the Century of Progress International Exposition World's Fair.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The theme of the fair was technological innovation over the century since Chicago's founding.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] During World War II, the city of Chicago alone produced more steel than the United Kingdom every year from 1939 – 1945, and more than Nazi Germany from 1943 – 1945.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Great Migration, which had been on pause due to the Depression, resumed at an even faster pace in the second wave, as hundreds of thousands of blacks from the South arrived in the city to work in the steel mills, railroads, and shipping yards.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] On December 2, 1942, physicist Enrico Fermi conducted the world's first controlled nuclear reaction at the University of Chicago as part of the top-secret Manhattan Project.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] This led to the creation of the atomic bomb by the United States, which it used in World War II in 1945.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Daley, a Democrat, was elected in 1955, in the era of machine politics.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1956, the city conducted its last major expansion when it annexed the land under O'Hare airport, including a small portion of DuPage County.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] By the 1960s, white residents in several neighborhoods left the city for the suburban areas – in many American cities, a process known as white flight – as Blacks continued to move beyond the Black Belt.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] While home loan discriminatory redlining against blacks continued, the real estate industry practiced what became known as blockbusting, completely changing the racial composition of whole neighborhoods.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Structural changes in industry, such as globalization and job outsourcing, caused heavy job losses for lower-skilled workers.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] At its peak during the 1960s, some 250,000 workers were employed in the steel industry in Chicago, but the steel crisis of the 1970s and 1980s reduced this number to just 28,000 in 2015.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1966, Martin Luther King Jr. and Albert Raby led the Chicago Freedom Movement, which culminated in agreements between Mayor Richard J.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Two years later, the city hosted the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention, which featured physical confrontations both inside and outside the convention hall, with anti-war protesters, journalists and bystanders being beaten by police.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Major construction projects, including the Sears Tower (now known as the Willis Tower, which in 1974 became the world's tallest building), University of Illinois at Chicago, McCormick Place, and O'Hare International Airport, were undertaken during Richard J.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1979, Jane Byrne, the city's first female mayor, was elected.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] She was notable for temporarily moving into the crime-ridden Cabrini-Green housing project and leading Chicago's school system out of a financial crisis.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1983, Harold Washington became the first black mayor of Chicago.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Washington's first term in office directed attention to poor and previously neglected minority neighborhoods.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] He was re‑elected in 1987 but died of a heart attack soon after.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Washington was succeeded by 6th ward alderperson Eugene Sawyer, who was elected by the Chicago City Council and served until a special election.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] His accomplishments included improvements to parks and creating incentives for sustainable development, as well as closing Meigs Field in the middle of the night and destroying the runways.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] After successfully running for re-election five times, and becoming Chicago's longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Daley declined to run for a seventh term.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1992, a construction accident near the Kinzie Street Bridge produced a breach connecting the Chicago River to a tunnel below, which was part of an abandoned freight tunnel system extending throughout the downtown Loop district.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The tunnels filled with 250 million US gallons (1,000,000 m3) of water, affecting buildings throughout the district and forcing a shutdown of electrical power.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The area was shut down for three days and some buildings did not reopen for weeks; losses were estimated at $1.95 billion.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] On February 23, 2011, Rahm Emanuel, a former White House Chief of Staff and member of the House of Representatives, won the mayoral election.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Emanuel was sworn in as mayor on May 16, 2011, and won re-election in 2015.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Lori Lightfoot, the city's first African American woman mayor and its first openly LGBTQ mayor, was elected to succeed Emanuel as mayor in 2019.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] All three city-wide elective offices were held by women (and women of color) for the first time in Chicago history: in addition to Lightfoot, the city clerk was Anna Valencia and the city treasurer was Melissa Conyears-Ervin.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] On May 15, 2023, Brandon Johnson assumed office as the 57th mayor of Chicago.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago is located in northeastern Illinois on the southwestern shores of freshwater Lake Michigan.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] It is the principal city in the Chicago Metropolitan Area, situated in both the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes region.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city rests on a continental divide at the site of the Chicago Portage, connecting the Mississippi River and the Great Lakes watersheds.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In addition to it lying beside Lake Michigan, two rivers—the Chicago River in downtown and the Calumet River in the industrial far South Side—flow either entirely or partially through the city.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago's history and economy are closely tied to its proximity to Lake Michigan.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] While the Chicago River historically handled much of the region's waterborne cargo, today's huge lake freighters use the city's Lake Calumet Harbor on the South Side.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The lake also provides another positive effect: moderating Chicago's climate, making waterfront neighborhoods slightly warmer in winter and cooler in summer.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] When Chicago was founded in 1837, most of the early building was around the mouth of the Chicago River, as can be seen on a map of the city's original 58 blocks.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The overall grade of the city's central, built-up areas is relatively consistent with the natural flatness of its overall natural geography, generally exhibiting only slight differentiation otherwise.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The average land elevation is 579 ft (176.5 m) above sea level.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] While measurements vary somewhat, the lowest points are along the lake shore at 578 ft (176.2 m), while the highest point, at 672 ft (205 m), is the morainal ridge of Blue Island in the city's far south side.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Lake Shore Drive runs adjacent to a large portion of Chicago's waterfront.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Some of the parks along the waterfront include Lincoln Park, Grant Park, Burnham Park, and Jackson Park.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] There are 24 public beaches across 26 miles (42 km) of the waterfront.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Landfill extends into portions of the lake providing space for Navy Pier, Northerly Island, the Museum Campus, and large portions of the McCormick Place Convention Center.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Most of the city's high-rise commercial and residential buildings are close to the waterfront.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] An informal name for the entire Chicago metropolitan area is "Chicagoland", which generally means the city and all its suburbs, though different organizations have slightly different definitions.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Major sections of the city include the central business district, called the Loop, and the North, South, and West Sides.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The three sides of the city are represented on the Flag of Chicago by three horizontal white stripes.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The North Side is the city's most densely populated residential section, and many high-rises are on this side of the city along the lakefront.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The South Side is the city's largest section, encompassing roughly 60% of its land area.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The South Side contains most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In the late 1920s, sociologists at the University of Chicago subdivided the city into 75 distinct community areas, plus O'Hare in 1956 and Edgewater in 1980 for a total of 77.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The community areas can further be subdivided into over 200 informally defined neighborhoods.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago's streets were laid out in a street grid that grew from the city's original townsite plot, which was bounded by Lake Michigan on the east, North Avenue on the north, Wood Street on the west, and 22nd Street on the south.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Streets following the Public Land Survey System section lines later became arterial streets in outlying sections.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] As new additions to the city were platted, city ordinance required them to be laid out with eight streets to the mile in one direction and sixteen in the other direction, about one street per 200 meters in one direction and one street per 100 meters in the other direction.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The grid's regularity provided an efficient means of developing new real estate property.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] A scattering of diagonal streets, many of them originally Native American trails, also cross the city (Elston, Milwaukee, Ogden, Lincoln, etc.).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Many additional diagonal streets were recommended in the Plan of Chicago, but only the extension of Ogden Avenue was ever constructed.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 2021, Chicago was ranked the fourth-most walkable large city in the United States.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Many of the city's residential streets have a wide patch of grass or trees between the street and the sidewalk itself.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] This helps to keep pedestrians on the sidewalk further away from the street traffic.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago's Western Avenue is the longest continuous urban street in the world.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Other notable streets include Michigan Avenue, State Street, 95th Street, Cicero Avenue, Clark Street, and Belmont Avenue.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The City Beautiful movement inspired Chicago's boulevards and parkways.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The destruction caused by the Great Chicago Fire led to the largest building boom in the history of the nation.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In 1885, the first steel-framed high-rise building, the Home Insurance Building, rose in the city as Chicago ushered in the skyscraper era, which would then be followed by many other cities around the world.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Today, Chicago's skyline is among the world's tallest and densest.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Some of the United States' tallest towers are located in Chicago; Willis Tower (formerly Sears Tower) is the third tallest building in the Western Hemisphere after One World Trade Center, and Central Park Tower.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Loop's historic buildings include the Chicago Board of Trade Building, the Fine Arts Building, 35 East Wacker, and the Chicago Building, 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments by Mies van der Rohe.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Many other architects have left their impression on the Chicago skyline such as Daniel Burnham, Louis Sullivan, Charles B.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Merchandise Mart, once the largest building in the world, had its own zip code until 2008, and stands near the junction of the North and South branches of the Chicago River.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Presently, the four tallest buildings in the city are Willis Tower (formerly the Sears Tower, also a building with its own zip code), Trump International Hotel and Tower, the Aon Center (previously the Standard Oil Building), and the John Hancock Center.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Industrial districts, such as some areas on the South Side, the areas along the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal, and the Northwest Indiana area are clustered.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago gave its name to the Chicago School and was home to the Prairie School, two movements in architecture.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Multiple kinds and scales of houses, townhouses, condominiums, and apartment buildings can be found throughout Chicago.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Large swaths of the city's residential areas away from the lake are characterized by brick bungalows built from the early 20th century through the end of World War II.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago is also a prominent center of the Polish Cathedral style of church architecture.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The Chicago suburb of Oak Park was home to famous architect Frank Lloyd Wright, who had designed The Robie House located near the University of Chicago.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] A popular tourist activity is to take an architecture boat tour along the Chicago River.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Chicago is famous for its outdoor public art with donors establishing funding for such art as far back as Benjamin Ferguson's 1905 trust.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] A number of Chicago's public art works are by modern figurative artists.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Some events which shaped the city's history have also been memorialized by art works, including the Great Northern Migration (Saar) and the centennial of statehood for Illinois.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Finally, two fountains near the Loop also function as monumental works of art: Plensa's Crown Fountain as well as Burnham and Bennett's Buckingham Fountain.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city mostly lies within the typical hot-summer humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfa*), and experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with frequent heat waves.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The July daily average temperature is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C), with afternoon temperatures peaking at 84.5 °F (29.2 °C).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] In a normal summer, temperatures reach at least 90 °F (32 °C) on 17 days, with lakefront locations staying cooler when winds blow off the lake.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Blizzards do occur, such as in winter 2011.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The normal winter high from December through March is about 36 °F (2 °C).
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] January and February are the coldest months.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] A polar vortex in January 2019 nearly broke the city's cold record of −27 °F (−33 °C), which was set on January 20, 1985.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Measurable snowfall can continue through the first or second week of April.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, short seasons, typically with low humidity.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Dew point temperatures in the summer range from an average of 55.8 °F (13.2 °C) in June to 61.7 °F (16.5 °C) in July.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] They can reach nearly 80 °F (27 °C), such as during the July 2019 heat wave.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] The city lies within USDA plant hardiness zone 6a, transitioning to 5b in the suburbs.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] According to the National Weather Service, Chicago's highest official temperature reading of 105 °F (41 °C) was recorded on July 24, 1934.
[src:american-institute-of-electrical-engineers/chicago-p01] Midway Airport reached 109 °F (43 °C) one day prior and recorded a heat index of 125 °F (52 °C) during the 1995 heatwave.
